<HEAD>U.S. Soldiers Fire at Cuban Guardpost, Prensa Latina Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with details, quotes, U.S. comment.
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soldiers at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> base at <LOCATION> Guantanamo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, fired two shots Thursday at <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> sentry posts, breaking glass but causing no injuries, the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Latina </ORGANIZATION> said. The news agency quoted a ministry statement as saying one shot was fired at 10 a.m. EST at sentry post 17, and a second at 1 p.m. at post 18. Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Satterfield </PERSON>, a spokesman in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` We received no reports of any such incident.'' Both shots shattered glass in the posts, the agency said in the dispatch, monitored in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. The direction indicated the shots were fired from <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> post 13, the agency quoted the note as saying. `` These actions are even more serious and of unpredictable consequences because the two shots hit the guardposts and could have wounded and even assassinated any of the soldiers who were on guard duty,'' the agency quoted the note as saying. The note said the last similar incident was Aug. 21, 1987, when shots were fired from <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> post 18 on a <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> observation post. It noted the incident occurred as the country was holding funerals for more than 2,000 Cuban soldiers and civilian technicians killed in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and other foreign conflicts the past 14 years. The ministry said it was not an accident that `` these vulgar and dangerous provocations by <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION> soldiers occurred precisely today.''
