<UNK>Ten Percent Of Publishers To Be Closed</UNK>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> plans to shut down 10 percent of its newspapers and publishing houses, targeting for closure those printing pornography or material critical of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> news agency said today. The agency quoted the current issue of <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> as saying newspaper and magazine offices that publish pornographic stories or articles running counter to the party line will lose their licenses. The Press and <ORGANIZATION> Publications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> will also merge newspapers and periodicals that are similar in content, it said. The report said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has 1,600 newspapers, 3,000 social science periodicals and 500 publishing houses. Many are similar in nature and have few readers. In the past year, particularly after <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> leaders used troops to crush the pro-democracy movement in June, the government has moved to consolidate and exert greater control over the publishing industry. Millions of publications have been confiscated and destroyed in a nationwide anti-pornography campaign and a number of publications that sympathized with the pro-democracy movement, such as <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>, have been shut down or revamped. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruihuan </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Politburo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> member in charge of propaganda and cultural affairs, said recently that many publications were being turned out that advocated `` bourgeois liberalization'', or Western ideas. He said such publications were `` full of seductive and poisonous material especially harmful to young people'' and `` it was high time to solve all these problems.''
</TEXT>
