<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     12-07 0856</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Beef Trade Undergoing Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The world's beef trade is undergoing rapid changes as production declines in 1989 and production falters in some major countries. One result, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday, is that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is edging ahead of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> as a world-class beef exporter. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports are estimated at 450,000 metric tons, up from 313,000 tons in 1988, the department's <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> reported. Exports are expected to rise to about 508,000 tons in 1990. Most of the increase is the result of larger sales to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> under last year's trade liberalization by <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> to open the door to more beef and citrus. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>'s total beef and veal exports, meanwhile, are estimated at 439,000 tons in 1989 and 368,000 tons in 1990. Production rose this year as drought forced more cattle to slaughter. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imports of beef, which reached 1.1 million tons in 1988, are expected to decline this year to around 990,000 tons, the report said. The decrease is the result of smaller shipments from <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, where production is down and more meat was diverted to the lucrative Japanese market. The report said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> beef imports in 1990 are likely to decline slightly, to around 970,000 tons, as <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> continues exporting to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. `` <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> beef exports grew at a faster rate than those of the other five countries during the 1980s, rising from sixth to fourth position by 1988,'' the report said. `` In 1989, it is expected that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will surpass <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> to become the third largest beef exporter in the world.'' The top six beef exporters in 1989 are: <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, 823,000 tons; the 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, 759,000; <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, 450,000; <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, 439,000; <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, 370,000; and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, 350,000. Overall, global beef and veal production is expected to decline this year to about 45.2 million metric tons from 45.3 million tons in 1988, the report said. Much of the decease occurred in the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. The situation in the major beef producing countries is watched closely by <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> trade analysts and livestock producers, particularly conditions in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>. Cattle herds are expected to increase in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> to about 25.3 million head by 1991 from 24.3 million at the beginning of 1989, the report said. `` Dampening a more rapid increase in the herd size is an attractive wool market and expansion in the sheep industry,'' the report said. `` Without this competition for resources, total cattle numbers could increase more rapidly.'' In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, drought forced cattle slaughter to about 3.3 million head this year from 3.1 million in 1988. But slaughter may decline to around 2.8 million head in 1990, the report said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says it will soon pay wheat and barley producers about $ 175 million in `` deficiency'' payments for participating in the government's 1989 acreage program. <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Bjerke </PERSON>, executive vice president of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said Wednesday that the payments to wheat and barley farmers will be made in cash through local offices of the <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stabilization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> Wheat payments will total about $ 168 million and barley $ 7 million. No payments will be made for 1989 oats. The payments will include a deduction for advance payments earlier this year. Deficiency payments are made to help make up the difference between a target price and the higher of the price support loan rate or a five-month market price average. For example, the target price for wheat this year is $ 4.10 per bushel and the basic loan rate is $ 2.57 per bushel. The market price average for five months was $ 3.78 per bushel. Thus, the deficiency payment rate would be 32 cents per bushel, the difference between the target and the market price. An advance of 25 cents per bushel was made, so farmers will get 7 cents per bushel at final settlement.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A reduction in the use of wheat as animal feed is partly responsible for a sharp jump in global corn trade, says the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. In the last four years, world corn shipments have increased an estimated 28 percent, the largest increase since the late 1970s, the department's <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday in a report. `` There has been some worldwide step-up in animal feeding, particularly in the -LRB- <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> -RRB- and major East Asian markets,'' the report said. `` But, in the last two years, an additional reason for the sharp expansion ... is the reduced use of wheat for feed, caused by relatively low global wheat supplies.'' As a result, wheat has become more expensive in relation to the livestock feeding value of corn. Further, the report said, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn exports have nearly doubled in the last few years, while exports of other foreign suppliers have dropped by one-third, due to `` shifts to more profitable crops like oilseeds, increased domestic utilization'' and poor crops. `` The net result is that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> now provides nearly 80 percent of the world's corn export needs, up dramatically from just a few years ago,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
