<HEAD>Supreme Court Considers `Right to Die' Issue</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruzan </PERSON> has watched with anguish for nearly seven years as his daughter lies unconscious in a <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> hospital and he says listening to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> consider her fate was yet another sad event. It `` certainly was a very painful thing to sit through,'' <PERSON> Cruzan </PERSON> said after the the justices heard arguments on whether his daughter's feeding tube should be removed. `` I would like to be able to express my feelings to them why we are very comfortable with our decision, why we feel that we are doing what <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> would want us to do,'' he said. <PERSON> Cruzan </PERSON>, a 55-year-old sheet metal worker from southwestern <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, and his wife, want the nation's highest court to grant their request for removal of a feeding tube sustaining their brain-damaged daughter, <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON>. On Wednesday, justices for the first time took up the `` right-to-die'' issue as they heard oral arguments by attorneys in the case of the 32-year-old woman, who has been in what doctors call a persistent vegetative state since a 1983 automobile accident. The <ORGANIZATION> Missouri </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has ruled that doctors can not remove the tube that supplies food and water keeping Ms. <PERSON> Cruzan </PERSON> alive. The family's attorney, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Colby </PERSON>, told the justices that if Ms. <PERSON> Cruzan </PERSON> were `` lucid for a moment and could come before this court,'' she would `` choose liberty'' and ask for removal of the feeding tube. But she will never recover to do that, he said. Assistant Attorney General <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Presson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> maintained that Ms. <PERSON> Cruzan </PERSON>'s parents have no right to permit their daughter's death, especially without `` clear and convincing evidence'' she would choose to die Letting her die `` goes against the state's interest in preventing suicide,'' he said. Solicitor General <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Starr </PERSON>, the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's top courtroom lawyer, supported the state's position. A ruling by the court is expected by July. The justices recently have been reluctant to expand individual rights, but they gave no clear sign on the outcome of the case as they questioned the lawyers during arguments. <PERSON> Colby </PERSON> said after the case that he did n't expect the court to issue a broad ruling on the the right-to-die question. An estimated 10,000 people in this country are being kept alive in a manner similar to that used for Ms. <PERSON> Cruzan </PERSON>. Legal and medical officials say the court's ruling could set a precedent in determining the limits of life-sustaining care. Doctors say Ms. <PERSON> Cruzan </PERSON> could live for 30 years or more in her current condition unless the feeding tube is removed. Her body is rigid, her hands and feet constricted and bent into claw shapes. She can breathe on her own and at times her eyes are open and move randomly. <PERSON> Cruzan </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON>, an older daughter and two grandchildren watched the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> proceedings. Afterward, he expressed concerns about the possible effects on other families if the high court denies his daughter a right to die. He contended it would force people to consider initially not ordering life-sustaining treatment for fear that it could not later be stopped. `` This puts families in a terrible situation of being faced with making a decision about life support when there is still hope, when it still might do some good,'' he said. Asked how he thought the oral arguments played out to the justices, <PERSON> Cruzan </PERSON> replied, `` I have no idea. I'm not an attorney. I'm just a spectator.''
