 Lawyers for a man convicted of operating a drug ring that took in $ 2 million a week in the nation's capital say they will appeal the verdict, while <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> says the convicted dealer will now face other charges. <PERSON> Rayful </PERSON> <PERSON> Edmond </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, 24, was convicted Wednesday of operating a cocaine distribution network that prosecutors said was responsible for up to 30 percent of the cocaine sold in the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>. A 12-member <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> jury found <PERSON> Edmond </PERSON> guilty of all seven charges against him after more than four days of deliberations, capping a 12-week trial held amid extremely tight security. The verdict means <PERSON> Edmond </PERSON> faces a mandatory life prison sentence. Ten other defendants were convicted of assisting him. `` Everyone on the defense team is upset by the verdict,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, one of <PERSON> Edmond </PERSON>'s attorneys. `` We had the cards stacked against us from the beginning ... and we are going to appeal.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Court Judge <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Richey </PERSON> has not yet set a sentencing date for <PERSON> Edmond </PERSON> or his associates. <PERSON> Edmond </PERSON> faces additional charges, including three counts of first-degree murder and conspiracy. <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> said he plans to try <PERSON> Edmond </PERSON> on those charges, despite the mandatory life sentence in the drug distribution case. `` Our immediate plan is to proceed,'' <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> said. `` The primary goal ... is to bring this organization to a halt.'' Prosecutors had described <PERSON> Edmond </PERSON>'s drug network as a blend of family members and close friends who conducted their operations with a sophisticated _ and deadly _ entrepreneurial flare. The charges against <PERSON> Edmond </PERSON> included conspiracy to violate drug laws, employing minors to possess and distribute cocaine, traveling across state lines to sell drugs and using a telephone to set up illegal drug deals. Convictions on those counts satisfy a definition of a continuing criminal enterprise, a crime that carries a mandatory life sentence. <PERSON> Edmond </PERSON>'s 10 co-defendants, including an aunt, a sister, a brother and several close friends, were found guilty of conspiracy to deal drugs. That crime carries a penalty of 10 years to life in prison. At its peak last summer, the prosecutors charged, the Edmond network was pumping up to 440 pounds of cocaine per week into the streets of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` The message should be clear _ if you deal death and destruction, you will pay with your life,'' <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> said. After noting that <PERSON> Edmond </PERSON> had been perceived by some friends and neighbors as a hero for his ability to make money, the prosecutor said <PERSON> Edmond </PERSON> should be seen instead as a `` purveyor of human destruction.'' The trial featured extremely strict security measures. At the outset, <PERSON> Richey </PERSON> ruled that jurors' names be kept secret even from himself and lawyers to protect the jury from reprisals. The home of one witness' mother was firebombed during the trial and an informant was shot after his name was accidentally divulged by the prosecution. Defense lawyer <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> suggested that the unusual security provisions _ including a 1 -LCB- - inch bullet-proof shield around the courtroom _ made it impossible for the defendants to receive a fair trial `` No matter what happened in that courtroom, it was going to make it very difficult to give Mr. <PERSON> Edmond </PERSON> the benefit of the doubt,'' he said.
