 The dollar rose against the Japanese yen in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> Thursday, while the key index on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> set another new high. The dollar closed at 144.13 yen, up 0.38 yen from Wednesday's close of 143.75 yen After opening at 143.95 yen, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency ranged between 143.94 and 144.33 yen. On the stock market, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues, which rose 160.12 points for a record closing of 37,654.29 Wednesday, added another 203.82 points, or 0.54 percent, to close at 37,858.11, another new high. Currency dealers said the dollar's bullish opening in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> was largely due to the currency's gains on overseas markets overnight. The dollar-buying was triggered by warnings issued by the East German military that it would not tolerate attempts by citizens to seize munitions from security installations, according to dealers. A fleeting fear that the military might take action to block the country's reform movement led some to sell the West German currency for dollars, they said. The dollar's decline against the mark in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> was accelerated overnight by comments from <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Undersecretary of the Treasury <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulford </PERSON>, who said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was `` not alarmed'' about the dollar's recent steep 10 percent decline against the mark. He also noted the dollar has only slipped 2 percent against the yen. The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> market took <PERSON> Mulford </PERSON>'s comments to mean that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> central bank has not been intervening to shore up the sagging dollar, as many had thought. Securities dealers said the Nikkei index rose as market players were reassured by an <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> announcement of 2.9 percent growth in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s real gross national product in the July-September quarter over the previous quarter. The rise in inflation-adjusted GNP was equivalent to an annual 12.2 percent growth, the largest since 1973, according to the agency. `` Trading is becoming more active and broader,'' said a dealer at <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, requesting anonymity. `` I expect the bullish trend to continue for some time.''
