<HEAD>Navy: Soviets Launch Aircraft From New Carrier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> can now launch ground-attack jets from its first full-scale aircraft carrier, a naval aviation advance that the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> says holds the potential for offensive use. The development came only days before <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> pressed President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on naval arms control issues at the <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> summit. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> confirmed on Wednesday that the 65,000-ton <LOCATION> Tbilisi </LOCATION> aircraft carrier had launched and recovered three fighter jets during trials in the <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> _ the MiG-29 Fulcrum, a SU-27 Flanker and the SU-25 Frogfoot ground attack aircraft. The <LOCATION> Tbilisi </LOCATION>'s capabilities are a marked advance over the much smaller Kiev-class carrier, which is capable of transporting only helicopters and jump-jets. While the <LOCATION> Tbilisi </LOCATION>'s sea trials are not unexpected, <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officials pointed to the type of aircraft used on the carrier as interesting _ as well as the timing of the event. `` They are way ahead of schedule,'' said one <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officer, who spoke on condition he not be identified by name. Use of an aircraft carrier vastly improves Soviet tactical aviation capabilities, allowing fighter jets to be launched far beyond the range of Soviet borders. The <LOCATION> Tbilisi </LOCATION> is the first of its class, while two others are under construction. The ship uses a `` ski jump'' bow to launch aircraft and not the high-powered catapults that hurl jets from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carriers. But the Soviets do use the arresting wires that stop planes as they land on the deck, just as the American carriers do. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, in a statement pointing to the ship's offensive capabilities, said: `` The Soviets have insisted that the <LOCATION> Tbilisi </LOCATION> ... -LRB- is -RRB- intended for defensive purposes only. ... Nonetheless, the demonstrated capability of the <LOCATION> Tbilisi </LOCATION> to accommodate a variant of one of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s principal ground-attack aircraft, the Frogfoot, shows a potential for offensive operations.'' While <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials said the trials took place in mid-November, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> confirmed them several days after <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> sought to ban short-range nuclear weapons aboard the superpowers' ships, according to <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> illustrated his concern over the wide-ranging <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, giving <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> a map of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> naval bases, deployments and maneuvers around the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. In rejecting <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s argument, said <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> maintained that `` the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is a land-based power. But the navy is crucial to us in terms of maintaining all of our commitments around the world, maintaining open sea lanes and commercial lanes around the world.'' Another defense official said the definition of the Soviet warship as an aircraft carrier is of some importance to the region. `` The Soviets continue to tell <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> that this is not an aircraft carrier,'' he said, adding that the Soviets contend it is a `` heavy aircraft-carrying cruiser.'' Under the 1936 <LOCATION> Montreux </LOCATION> Convention, <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> could bar the movement of such a warship through the Dardanelles, which is the passage between the <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>, the official said. The convention put the control of the water passage in Turkish hands, and it allows the nation to close the straits to warships of other nations in time of war. The Soviets have stated that the <LOCATION> Tbilisi </LOCATION> will join the <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fleet </ORGANIZATION> and operate out of the <LOCATION> Kola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> said.
