<HEAD>Baker Clears First Hurdle to Mideast Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> still faces tough problems in getting <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION> peace talks started, even with the conditional acceptance by the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> of a first round of negotiations. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> will be able to convene talks in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> early next year with the foreign ministers of <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. However, going beyond that stage will take slick maneuvering by <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> as well as concessions from all sides. The <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>, speaking through <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, agreed Wednesday to the session. The Israeli Cabinet agreed last month. But <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials made it clear that the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> still have reservations about what happens next, and <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> will have to find a way to ease their concerns to keep going. Basically, <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s group is clinging to its claim to represent Palestinians everywhere. It wants to play a role in selecting the <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> delegation that would meet with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION> as the next step in a drawn-out peace process. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, on the other hand, wants to exclude the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> even from a behind-the-scenes role. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>'s five-point program guarantees that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> will go to <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION> only `` after a satisfactory list of Palestinians has been worked out.'' But another provision of the <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> plan specifies that <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> can not substitute itself for the <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> and that it `` will consult with Palestinians on all aspects of the dialogue.'' That could mean the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> will be able to play an influential role even if it's not at the table. Despite the problems, though, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> achieved a breakthrough of sorts after three months of dickering with Foreign Ministers <PERSON> Moshe </PERSON> <PERSON> Arens </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Esmat </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdel </PERSON> <PERSON> Meguid </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>. They will continue the bargaining at the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> meeting, which <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> said would be held in January, at the earliest. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goal is to carry out a proposal by <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> for elections among the 1.4 million Palestinians who live on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>. The elected Palestinians would negotiate with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> an arrangement for limited self-rule. After the five-year experiment, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and Palestinians would hold talks on an overall settlement. The <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> has repeatedly denounced the Israeli scenario as a scheme to undercut Palestinian aspirations for statehood. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> telephoned <PERSON> Arens </PERSON> with the news of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s conditional acceptance. <PERSON> Arens </PERSON> told him the Israeli government would study the response, said <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaron </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the Israeli Embassy. A senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official, declining to be identified, said that now that <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> has qualified acceptance from the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> `` he can get down to work on dealing with their views.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> three months ago began an arduous diplomatic effort to bridge the gap between the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. His plan includes the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> meeting with <PERSON> Arens </PERSON> and <PERSON> Meguid </PERSON>. Another provision of his five-point program, released by Ms. <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON>, is that `` the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> understands that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> will attend the dialogue only after a satisfactory list of Palestinians has been worked out.'' A third provision guarantees that <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> will consult with Palestinians `` on all aspects of the dialogue.'' A fourth assures the Palestinians that those who meet with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> `` would be free to raise issues that relate to their opinions on how to make elections and the negotiating process succeed.'' This could be a vehicle for Palestinians to assert statehood aspirations and also to register demands extending beyond the limited self-rule <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> envisions for five years on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>. For the past two years, <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> in the territories have clashed with <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> authorities. At least 626 have died in the process, while 155 other Palestinians were killed by Arabs on suspicion of cooperating with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Also, 43 Israeli soldiers and civilians died in the rebellion. The Baker formula makes no direct reference to the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>, with which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOC