<HEAD>Former U.S. Negotiator Urges Deep Cuts In Strategic Missiles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should press for additional cuts in strategic nuclear weapons once it finishes negotiating a pact to reduce those weapons by as much as half, a former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arms negotiator says. `` Certainly we can afford to be more ambitious in our arms control proposals,'' former arms negotiator <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Warnke </PERSON> said Wednesday in a speech to the <ORGANIZATION> Arms </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a private research group. Under the START -LRB- Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty -RRB- agreement now being negotiated, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet long-range bombers, missiles and submarines would be cut by 30 percent to 50 percent. <PERSON> Warnke </PERSON> said that agreement could be completed and signed at the summit President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> plan to hold in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> next June, a meeting the two leaders agreed to at the <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> Summit last week. `` There is no reason at all we ca n't go ahead with a START 2 treaty,'' <PERSON> Warnke </PERSON> said. Such a second treaty should aim at banning missiles with multiple warheads, <PERSON> Warnke </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Warnke </PERSON> argued that Soviet troop withdrawals from <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the political changes sweeping the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact countries mean fewer nuclear weapons are needed to defend the West. He said the major obstacle in the strategic arms reduction talks in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> was the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> program to devise a space shield against ballistic missile attack. `` But that idea left town with Mr. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Warnke </PERSON> said of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Initiative </ORGANIZATION> championed by the former president but viewed with skepticism by many in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and most arms control experts. A ban on missiles with multiple warheads would eliminate the threat of a nuclear first strike by either side, <PERSON> Warnke </PERSON> suggested. Such an attack would require so many single-warhead missiles the aggressor would be unable to defend against nuclear retaliation _ and therefore would not launch an attack, he argued. But <PERSON> Warnke </PERSON>, who was former President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>'s chief negotiator, stressed the two sides should complete the current START treaty first before making deeper cuts in their strategic weapons. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has approved a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration plan to extend the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arsenal of land-based missiles armed with multiple warheads that could reach all targets within the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> by putting some on rail cars that could move around in a crisis, making them harder for the Soviets to destroy. <PERSON> Warnke </PERSON> said that `` probably was a lousy idea'' and would escalate nuclear tensions.
