<HEAD>`Bear Man of Pack Creek' Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Price </PERSON>, who became a symbol of peaceful coexistence between humans and brown bears, has died of cancer. He was 90. Price, known as the `` bear man of <LOCATION> Pack </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>,'' died Tuesday at the home of his great-nephew, <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Lingle </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Juneau </LOCATION>, where he had been living since October. He lived for 40 years along the shores of <LOCATION> Pack </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> Admiralty </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, which attracts thousands of visitors to see the world's largest concentration of brown bears. But Price himself also was an attraction _ a small, white-haired man who casually strolled among the fearsome-looking bruins, which can weigh more than 1,000 pounds, with nothing more than a walking stick for protection. A native of <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, Price arrived in southeast <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> in 1927 in a sailboat he had built in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. In 1928, he set up a mining and logging operation at <LOCATION> Windham </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> not far from <LOCATION> Pack </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>, 30 miles south of <LOCATION> Juneau </LOCATION>. He also worked as a mechanic, fisherman and fox farmer. In the 20 years that he regularly visited his great-uncle, <PERSON> Lingle </PERSON> said he always felt safe walking with Price because of the special relationship he had with the bears. `` He always said if you're friends with the bears, the bears will be friends with you,'' <PERSON> Lingle </PERSON> said. `` He had a mutual respect with the bears and the proof is that he lived there for 40 years with only one incident.'' That occurred on a narrow path between Price's woodshed and his house on a beach. Price and a brown bear surprised each other and a face off began with neither backing down. The big brownie finally swatted Price, breaking his collarbone. Despite living in close quarters with about 25 brown bears that roam the <LOCATION> Pack </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> area, Price never carried a rifle. A quick bop on the nose with his walking stick was usually sufficient if a bear got testy. As word of Price's special relationship with the bears spread, films, television shows and magazines told his story. During the 1980s, the number of visitors to <LOCATION> Pack </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> increased dramatically. `` He had a gentleness and a special way of communicating with the bears,'' said <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Juneau </LOCATION> wildlife filmmaker and <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> of Game member. `` He did n't subscribe to the theory that they were marauding killers lurking behind every tree.'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said Price would walk to within 6 feet of the animals and talk to them. `` This is the passing of a grand old man that represents a unique part of the heritage of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. `` His legacy is that people can coexist with wildlife peacefully if we try. He taught that by example.'' Survivors include Price's second wife, <PERSON> Esther </PERSON>, who lives in <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> and has Alzheimer's disease, <PERSON> Lingle </PERSON> said. His first wife died of cancer.
