<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The swapping of classified <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> budget documents by employees of nine major defense contractors was `` endemic,'' according to a witness at the federal trial of a former <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> employee. The informal network of document trading existed in the late 1970s and early 1980s, government witnesses said Wednesday. It was the third day of the trial of <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> worker accused of illegally obtaining secret <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> documents. <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON> has pleaded innocent to 39 counts, including conspiracy, illegal conveyance of classified documents and mail fraud. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> earlier pleaded guilty to receiving classified documents and will pay a $ 5.2 million fine. Among the companies implicated in the document trading network besides <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> were <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Bendix </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>, RCA, <ORGANIZATION> Grumman </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Raytheon </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Marietta </PERSON>. `` I would describe it as endemic,'' <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Coutre </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Bendix </LOCATION> employee from 1972 to 1984, said of the document swaps. Ms. <PERSON> Coutre </PERSON> said everyone seemed to have the so-called `` planning, programming and budget system'' documents and she exchanged documents with <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON> and employees of other defense companies. The documents were never entered in <PERSON> Bendix </PERSON>'s classified document log, Ms. <PERSON> Coutre </PERSON> said, adding that she kept the documents in a file cabinet or a safe and when they became outdated she would shred them or burn them in her fireplace. Ms. <PERSON> Coutre </PERSON> said she never asked <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON> or others where they got the documents. `` It was an unspoken agreement that no one asked that question,'' she said. `` We did n't want to get people in trouble.'' Ms. <PERSON> Coutre </PERSON>, who was granted immunity from prosecution by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorneys, said the documents gave defense contractors some indication of how serious the Pentagon was about pursuing various projects. `` They were used primarily to support business decisions,'' she said. `` We had to look at the opportunities from the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> and make decisions on whether to invest money. We wanted to make sure the government was serious about the opportunities before we went forward.'' <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, an RCA employee from 1979 to 1984, said he also swapped documents, but the top source of supply was <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON>'s supply of documents `` seemed to be continuous and quick'' and on at least two occasions <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON> handed him documents from the trunk of his car parked in the garage at <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Rosslyn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, office. `` It was my sense that every major contractor had them,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who was also granted immunity from prosecution, said he `` never asked anyone what their source was. It was just not done. It was not the gentlemanly way to do things.'' But <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said he had the `` distinct impression'' that <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON> got the documents from the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> and he thought <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON> was encouraging others in the network to develop <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> sources. <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON>, who worked both for <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Marietta </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>, said that he too swapped documents with <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON> and others. <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON>, who was called as a defense witness, said he did n't feel that exchanging the classified documents was illegal and that defense contractors had a legitimate right to know what was in the documents <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> said <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON> was described by others as the `` best in the business'' in terms of getting the documents, but denied that he had heard <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON> described as the `` mother lode.'' In earlier testimony Wednesday, a retired <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> employee said he and other company employees were under pressure to get the secret budget documents. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lozito </PERSON> said when he was asked by his supervisor to get classified <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> budget documents he turned to <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON>, an old friend, for help. <PERSON> Lozito </PERSON>, who also was granted immunity, said he got documents from <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON> five or 10 times a year, from 1979 to early 1984.
