<FIRST>r a PM-NorthwestQuakes     12-07 0743</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest Quakes,0764</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pacific Northwest Due for Giant Quake, Studies Suggest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Growing evidence shows a monstrous earthquake could wallop the woefully unprepared <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>, followed by tidal waves that would swamp coastal areas of <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, scientists say. `` The chances are very high that a great earthquake will occur, yet seismic building codes are notoriously out of date,'' said <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> geophysicist <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON>. <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Geological Survey geophysicist in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, called the region's ability to prevent death and damage from earthquakes `` abysmal.'' `` We're not prepared in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION>,'' he said. While some scientists remain skeptical, evidence accumulated during the last five years indicates six quakes with magnitudes of 8 to 9 rocked the region during the past 3,500 years, making coastal areas suddenly drop so that tsunamis, or seismic tidal waves, inundated the shoreline. The last such quake was about 300 years ago. More studies showing such quakes have occurred and are likely to strike again were released Wednesday during the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geophysical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>'s fall meeting. Residents of the <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> `` should be ready for an earthquake at any time,'' although no one knows how soon, <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON> said. One study found the <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> coast near <LOCATION> Tillamook </LOCATION> has been rising and tilting eastward much more quickly during the past 50 years than it has on average in 80,000 to 100,000 years. That indicates that stress is building underground, and will be released in a quake measuring 8 to 9 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale any time within the next 150 years, according to scientists from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>. The study was conducted by <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Weldon </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON> at <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>. Dozens of dead western cedar trees along <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s southern coast were studied by <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Yamaguchi </PERSON>, a forester at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Boulder </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Yamaguchi </PERSON> said that by dating the trees' rings, he determined they all died suddenly about 300 years ago, when coastal land suddenly dropped during a major quake and tsunamis submerged the trees <PERSON> Yamaguchi </PERSON> said the trees were found along a 60-mile coastal stretch, suggesting the quake measured 8 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Reinhart </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> presented a study showing 300-year-old peat buried by sand has been found along at least a 120-mile stretch of the Oregon-Washington coast. She said it indicates a 40-foot-high tsunami dumped sand on coastal estuaries in a big quake three centuries ago. <PERSON> Richards </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> is severely unprepared for the `` great seismic hazard.'' The lack of recent big quakes lulled Oregonians into a false sense of security, and the state has made little progress updating building codes to take large quakes into account, he added. <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state is slightly better prepared because building standards were improved after a magnitude-7 .1 quake in <LOCATION> Olympia </LOCATION> in 1949 and a magnitude-6 .5 quake near <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> in The two quakes killed 17 people. Geological Survey geologist <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckham </PERSON> found new evidence that one and possibly two quakes measuring about 7 rocked <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> at least 1,200 years ago. He found that land on <LOCATION> Bainbridge </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> west of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> was suddenly uplifted by as much as 23 feet at the time. A magnitude-7 .3 quake in <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> several years ago raised land there by about 16 feet Two large plates of Earth's crust collide off the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION>. The Juan de Fuca plate, which is under the seafloor, is diving eastward under the North American plate beneath <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in a process is called subduction. Quakes can happen in subduction zones when one plate sticks to the other until so much stress builds up they snap apart in a giant temblor. That caused the 1985 <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> earthquakes, which killed about 10,000 people, and the two largest quakes ever recorded: the 1960 <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> quake that killed about 5,000 people and measured 9.5, and the 1964 <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> quake that claimed 131 lives and measured 9.2. <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Sykes </PERSON>, of <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Lamont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Doherty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Observatory </ORGANIZATION>, said other scientists `` have too quickly jumped on the big earthquake scenario'' for the Northwest. He believes the <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuca </PERSON> plate is warmer and softer than the plates off <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>. In that case, the plate could dive smoothly under <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> without sticking and snapping. But <PERSON> Richards </PERSON> said if that were true, the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> would have `` the only major subduction zone which does not cause substantial earthquakes.''
