<HEAD>Former Allies Now Foes in Election for Leland's Congressional Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN FAHLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two former allies on <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Leland </PERSON>'s `` People's Five'' slate of young, black legislative candidates have become political foes in the race to succeed the congressman who died in a plane crash State Sen. <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> and City Councilman <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> face eachother in Saturday's non-partisan runoff election for <PERSON> Leland </PERSON>'s 18th Congressional District seat. <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> was killed Aug. 7 during a famine relief mission to <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>. In the early 1970s, all three men worked for civil rights, fair housing, health care for the poor, food for the hungry and other social concerns. They were the only successful candidates from the Democratic `` People's Five'' slate, who sought to represent <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> in the state House. Now <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> have spent weeks trying to establish their political differences and prove their interest in representing a district said to be among the nation's poorest. `` My campaign is a movement,'' said <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` It's an opportunity for people to get involved in politics again.'' An attorney and a former law school instructor, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, 48, has been state senator since 1983 after serving 10 years in the House. He captured 41 percent of the vote in the Nov. 7 election, compared with 34 percent for Hall. The two topped a field of 11 candidates seeking to succeed <PERSON> Leland </PERSON>. The term expires in 1990. `` I won in the black community and the white community and the Hispanic community,'' <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said. `` And I intend to do exactly the same thing on Dec. 9.'' A poll published Monday by <ORGANIZATION> KPRC-TV </ORGANIZATION> showed the race is nearly deadlocked. The <ORGANIZATION> KPRC </ORGANIZATION> poll said 41 percent of voters favor <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, while 38 percent were for <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Twenty-one percent said they were undecided, and the poll had a 5 point margin of error. Hall, 45, has a more buttoned-down style. Also an attorney, he gained early notice as a decorated <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veteran who returned to <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> questioning discriminatory practices in housing and employment. More recently, he has worked to set up 50 `` Just Say No'' anti-drug programs for 1,300 students. `` I have a vision that indeed we can do better than we do now at solving the problems that we face as a community,'' said <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, a three-term legislator who has served as councilman since 1979. Hall, who had been a high school friend of <PERSON> Leland </PERSON>'s, lost a bitter battle to him for the congressional seat in 1978, when the two fought to succeed <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON>. Hall had to give up his re-election bid for the council to run for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Mayor <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitmire </PERSON> has endorsed his bid for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and helped him raise money. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> agree many issues: both favor increased funding to battle drug trafficking and abuse, and for health care to the poor and elderly and military cutbacks in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. `` What differences there are largely is a matter of style,'' says <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, a political scientist at <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> comes off as the more grassroots kinds of campaigner _ more of the people's candidate. While Hall has the more polished image, as the sort of professional candidate. But both of them are extremely professional and long-term political people.''
