<FIRST>r i PM-France-Immigration     12-07 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-France-Immigration,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>Success of Right Prompts New Immigration Task Force</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK McDOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stung by electoral successes of the extreme right and fierce debate over rights for Moslems, the government has appointed a trouble-shooter to formulate new policy for integrating immigrants into French society. Premier <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> on Wednesday named <PERSON> Hubert </PERSON> <PERSON> Prevot </PERSON> as permanent secretary of a government committee that will grapple with what has become the leading issue in domestic politics. `` The economic situation of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> no longer permits us to be a land of immigration,'' government spokesman <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pensec </PERSON> said after the appointment was announced at the weekly Cabinet meeting. `` It's now a question of integrating foreigners who have come to make their homes here and wish to live here permanently,'' <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pensec </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Prevot </PERSON>, 61, will head a task force of 13 ministers to grapple with the issues of integrating Moslems into the secular school system, the definition of a political refugee, illegal workers and immigrant housing. The panel will submit conclusions to the government sometime after Jan. 31. The creation of the task force represents a victory for the extreme-right <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> headed by <PERSON> Jean-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>, who has fulfilled a long-held goal of putting immigration high on the government's agenda. It comes the same day <PERSON> Marie-France </PERSON> <PERSON> Stirbois </PERSON> took the party's first seat in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> since electoral reforms in 1988 Mrs. <PERSON> Stirbois </PERSON> won the seat for suburban <ORGANIZATION> Dreux </ORGANIZATION> in a runoff election Sunday. Immigration exploded into a front-page issue in October after three girls with North African origins insisted on wearing Islamic scarves to their junior high school. French law dating to the turn of the century separates church and state. All forms of proselytizing and wearing of religious symbols are prohibited in the secular school system. Though two of the girls removed their scarves and returned to class on Saturday, they ignited fresh debate over whether some immigrants can be absorbed into French culture. <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> has pushed the issue for years, arguing that social payments to immigrants cut into benefits for native French citizens. His party fares well in areas like <LOCATION> Dreux </LOCATION> that have a high population of non-European immigrants. In an interview published in Wednesday's edition of the conservative newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Le </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Figaro </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> urged the government to expel all foreigners who arrived in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> after 1974. <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> says a law passed that year that restricted immigration to political asylum or reuniting families is widely flouted. `` Wisdom would dictate reducing the number of foreigners in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and reversing the flood,'' <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> was quoted as saying. `` In 10 years there will be 100 million people living in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. What is their hope? To come to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>.'' He continued: `` Is that the solution? Of course not. The solution is the development of the underdeveloped countries.'' The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> has won 9 to 14.5 percent of the vote nationwide vote in recent elections. The debate over immigration almost never mentions immigrants from <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, but focuses instead on <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and black <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, where many countries are former French colonies or protectorates. A survey of 926 people conducted by the polling service <ORGANIZATION> BVA </ORGANIZATION> showed 68 percent of the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> think the level of tolerance has been reached for immigration, and 50 percent oppose the construction of new mosques. The last national census, taken in 1982, showed 3.6 million immigrants living in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. The Ministry of the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> puts the current figure at 4.5 million, or about 8 percent of a total population of 55 million. The ministry's last breakdown, in 1985, showed <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> as the most numerous immigrant population at 846,488, followed by Algerians at 725,049, Moroccans at 558,799, Italians at 378,339, Spaniards at 353,232, Tunisians at 225,730 and Turks at 160,140.
