<HEAD>Major Terrorist Violence in Colombia Since August</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Major terrorist attacks, including bombings and assassinations, since the government's offensive against drug traffickers began Aug. 18: Aug. 25 _ Bombs explode at <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> offices in <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION>, and terrorists burn the country homes of a former finance minister and a senator. One person dies in the attack on the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> office. Police deactivate bombs placed at the <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> offices of two radio networks. Sept. 2 _ A car bomb explodes at a gas station beside the <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> offices of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Espectador </LOCATION> newspaper, injuring two people. Sept. 25 _ A bomb explodes in the sixth floor of the Hilton Hotel in <LOCATION> Cartagena </LOCATION>, killing two doctors attending a conference and injuring five people. Sept. 27 _ A car bomb explodes at a gas station in <LOCATION> Suba </LOCATION>, less than 15 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>, killing two people and injuring five. Sept. 28 _ About 60 cars are damaged as a car bomb explodes in the parking lot of the Tequendama Hotel in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>. Oct. 16 _ Four people die and nine are injured when a car bomb explodes at the <ORGANIZATION> Vanguardia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> newspaper offices in the city of <LOCATION> Bucaramanga </LOCATION>. About 80 percent of the building is destroyed and nearby stores are damaged. The Extraditables, a group linked to the <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> cartel, claims responsibility for the attack on the paper. Oct. 17 _ Gunmen kill a federal judge, <PERSON> Hector </PERSON> <PERSON> Jimenez </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>, in front of his <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> home. The Extraditables claim responsibility. Oct. 18 _ A hand grenade carried by a terrorist explodes accidentally in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>'s main plaza, killing the man and injuring four people. The terrorist had tried to enter the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> but was stopped by security guards. Oct. 20 _ The Royal Hotel in the city of <LOCATION> Barranquilla </LOCATION> is targeted in a car bomb attack that injures six people. Oct. 24 _ Five police officers are killed and 16 injured when terrorists set off a bomb beside a bus carrying officers to their posts in <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION>. Nov. 2 _ A car bomb explodes under a <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> bridge, killing four people and injuring two. Nov. 27 _ An <ORGANIZATION> Avianca </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 crashes shortly after takeoff from <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>, killing all 107 people aboard. Government investigators later say a bomb aboard the plane caused the crash. Dec. 5 _ Gunmen assassinate another judge, <PERSON> Bernardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaramillo </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION>. The judge was handling several murder cases in which drug traffickers were the principal suspects. Dec. 6 _ A truck bomb packing hundreds of pounds of dynamite explodes in front of the offices of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s federal investigative police, killing at least 40 people. Hundreds are injured.
