<HEAD>New York Survey: Almost All Supermarket Scanners Overcharge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Customers of supermarkets with automatic checkout scanners were overcharged in 32 of the 33 stores checked by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state inspectors this year, officials said. The 32 stores, which include all of the major supermarket chains, were fined a total of $ 5,015 for the violations, said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferrara </PERSON>, assistant director of food inspection services for the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> and Markets. More than 5 percent of the items in a typical store are mispriced in favor of the supermarket, <PERSON> Ferrara </PERSON> said. Nonetheless, state officials were unable to say Wednesday whether the customers at the 32 stores ended up net winners or losers because of the scanners. Industry officials noted that the scanners might also be undercharging customers on some of the many items checked in each supermarket. `` I think they -LRB- consumers -RRB- have to pay careful attention to the prices marked as opposed to the prices on the scanners,'' <PERSON> Ferrara </PERSON> said. `` It's not uncommon for them to be overcharged for items in stores that use scanners. I guess ` buyer beware' would probably be good advice.'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosen </PERSON>, director of government relations for the state <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merchants </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said mistakes are made that both benefit and hurt consumers. So while 32 of the 33 stores were found to be overcharging on some items, they may have been undercharging on many others, said the lobbyist. `` People are n't going to knowingly cheat their customers because they'll lose them,'' <PERSON> Rosen </PERSON> said. `` You might fool someone once or twice, but if you lose that person and they never come back, you're not going to be in business for very long. <PERSON> Ferrara </PERSON> said inspectors, posing as customers, would go into stores and buy about 150 items or more, comparing prices on the product with the receipt after checking out. Stores where discrepancies were found that hurt the consumers were fined. Many of the mistakes came in items that were advertised as on sale, but the sale price had n't been entered into the computer scanner, he said.
