<HEAD>Indications of Widespread Security Lapses at Nuclear Arms Plants</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf, `Security questions ...,' to INSERT first
reference to Dingell; picks up final graf, `Also, a ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Congressional investigators are turning up evidence of possibly widespread security problems at the Energy Department's nuclear weapons plants, which already are under the gun for extensive safety and environmental flaws. Little has been documented of security lapses, mainly because details about protection of plutonium and other nuclear materials are classified. As a result of congressional inquiries, however, once-secret information is trickling out. Some members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and private experts say the emerging evidence points to an unnerving vulnerability to diversion of bomb-grade plutonium to terrorists. `` The questions of diversion and the pathways of diversion are extremely numerous,'' said <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoenig </PERSON>, scientific director of the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a private group that advocates measures to control the spread of nuclear weapons. Despite the government's devotion to secrecy in matters of nuclear weapon production, it appears some federal nuclear facilities have run the risk in recent years of allowing the theft of enough plutonium to build a nuclear bomb. Government documents also suggest that some <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials have played down protection problems. Other officials complain that budget constraints have prevented the department from filling security posts with adequately trained people. Among security slips disclosed this week by a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> investigations subcommittee: _ <ORGANIZATION> Argonne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory-West </ORGANIZATION>, near <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, violated rules last year on controlling access to portable plutonium at a nuclear reactor site at the lab Details of the incident are classified, but a senior <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official told a closed hearing of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> investigations subcommittee that the violation `` revealed a deficiency and vulnerability'' to diversion of bomb materials to terrorists. Portions of the hearing transcript were declassified earlier this week. The official, <PERSON> Hilary </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rauch </PERSON>, manager of the regional <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> office that manages the <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> facility, did not dispute a suggestion by Rep. <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Sikorski </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Minn </LOCATION>., that the incident meant `` people could be carting plutonium out of the place. <PERSON> Rauch </PERSON> stressed that the problem has since been corrected. _ Quantities of plutonium large enough to make a nuclear bomb were left unattended in rooms without alarms at <ORGANIZATION> Lawrence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Livermore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> last spring A previously secret inspection report on <PERSON> Livermore </PERSON> also said large quantities of plutonium `` were often left, between process steps, with only one person or unattended'' during normal business hours. Department officials acknowledged to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee that this was a serious lapse of security. _ A senior department official, Brig Gen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kavanaugh </PERSON>, expressed concern in an internal memorandum last April at the frequency of `` marginal and unsatisfactory ratings'' of nuclear material security by federal inspectors of weapons plants. `` If, within the DOE, we can not articulate and enforce effective security practices at our most sensitive facilities, we will deserve the comments of our most vocal critics,'' wrote <PERSON> Kavanaugh </PERSON>, who left the department shortly after sending his memo. <PERSON> Kavanaugh </PERSON> also drafted a tough-worded message that he suggested be sent to managers of key weapons plants requiring immediate action to improve nuclear materials security. A few weeks later, a brief version of his proposed message was sent offering thanks for previous efforts but making scant mention of the problems. The subcommittee is investigating why the draft <PERSON> Kavanaugh </PERSON> message was watered down by his superiors. Security questions also have arisen at the <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION> weapons complex in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>. Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., expressed alarm that responsibility for granting security clearances was taken away from <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION>'s security officials and given to the personnel office Also, a laboratory at <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION> was unsure for more than a year, starting in August 1988, whether a substantial amount of tritium _ a gas used to make nuclear warheads _ had been stolen from a loading facility. The department said last week that it was confident that none had been lost, but some members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> say doubts remain about <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION>'s ability to protect tritium supplies.
