<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President F.W. <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON> announced a major defense cutback today, including a reduction from two years to one year of the mandatory period of initial military service for white men. He said certain military units would be eliminated and facilities closed, with details to be disclosed next year. The announcement came two weeks after <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> completed the withdrawal of its troops from <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, where since 1966 they had fought a bush war against pro-independence guerrillas. A year ago, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> signed a treaty that cleared the way for <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s independence and also halted South African involvement in the civil war in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s northern neighbor. These diplomatic developments have prompted speculation that a major cut in military spending is imminent. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON>, opening a new headquarters for the state arms manufacturing corporation, indicated that conscripts already in the military would have their terms of service shortened. He said details about this would be disclosed Friday. The president said it was possible that career military personnel and employees of <ORGANIZATION> Armscor </ORGANIZATION>, the weapons company, might lose their jobs as part of the cutback. He said efforts would be made to find new jobs for these people. It was the second time in 10 days that the president had announced steps which reduce the scope of military operations and influence. On Nov. 28, he scrapped a nationwide security network which critics had denounced as an unaccountable shadow government. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON>'s predecessor, P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, had been criticized for giving the security forces too large a role in policy-making. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> quit in August after losing a power struggle with de Klerk. Under the current conscription system, all able-bodied white males in South African are required to serve two years of initial military duty and then are eligible for call-up camps that could amount to two more years of service spread out over 20 or more years. Military service for blacks, Asians and people of mixed-race is voluntary. In September, 780 white men vowed not to perform military service, the largest defiance ever of conscription laws. Draft resisters face prison terms of up to six years, or 1 -LCB- times the amount of unfulfilled service. Three men currently are serving six-year terms _ the youngest, 19-year-old <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Bester </PERSON>, completed a full year of his sentence on Tuesday. The government does not release information on the manpower of the armed forces. However, at any given time in recent years, there have been as estimated 68,000 conscripts on active duty and about 325,000 men in the reserves out of the roughly 2.4 million white males of all ages in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>.
