<BYLINE>By LISA ZAGAROLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The state <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> has passed a bill requiring parental consent for unmarried girls under age 18 to have an abortion in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. The bill passed 65-39 Wednesday after the house rejected nearly 50 amendments, including one to require boys to wear condoms to prevent teen-age pregnancy. It now goes to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, which has passed a similar measure and is expected to take action before lawmakers leave for the winter holidays next week. That sets up a promised veto by Gov. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Blanchard </PERSON>, who has pledged to strike down any measure restricting abortion rights. Opponents of the bill say it is merely intended to make it more difficult for girls to get an abortion. Planned Parenthood officials said at least 70 percent of pregnant minors in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> already bring at least one parent to an abortion clinic with them. `` This bill is meant to put the squeeze on teen-agers with no regard to the horrible alternatives they may seek,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Maxine </PERSON> <PERSON> Berman </PERSON>, a Democrat. `` Can any of you live with yourself if a woman resorts to a back-alley abortion, or to crack cocaine to induce abortion, or to suicide? I do n't want any more young people to die.'' Under the legislation, a pregnant girl could petition a probate court to have an abortion if she believes she ca n't tell a parent or if the parent refuses to let her have an abortion. Permission would be required from just one of the parents. `` We're talking about the very bedrock of our society _ family,'' said Democratic Rep. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>, the bill's sponsor. `` We recognize there are families in trouble, that's why we put the judicial bypass in there.'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Kandler </PERSON>, spokesman for <PERSON> Blanchard </PERSON>, said the Democratic governor would n't change his mind despi