<HEAD>One Year After Quake, Armenians Mourn The Dead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LENINAKAN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bells tolled and mournful chants filled the streets today as <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> marked the one-year anniversary of the earthquake that killed at least 25,000 people. In this mountain city hit hardest by the quake, officials stopped the big town clock forever at 11:41, the minute disaster struck Dec. 7, 1988. `` If only it could all have been a dream, and we could wake up and have everyone here again,'' Armenian poet <PERSON> Maro </PERSON> <PERSON> Marzarian </PERSON> told a crowd of several hundred gathered to dedicate a memorial to <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION>'s victims. In a cemetery just outside town, hundreds of families gathered at gravesites, some openly sobbing, others in stony silence. Among the many graves of the earthquake victims were plots for the remains of unidentifiable corpses, with markers reading only `` 238 woman'' or `` 453 child.'' `` Your soul hurts so much you just ca n't express it,'' said <PERSON> Lilia </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepanian </PERSON>, 25, whose brother, <PERSON> Zillik </PERSON>, and his family were crushed to death in their <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION> apartment. `` You remember that on this day, at this time, they were already gone,'' she said. `` At this time one year ago I was standing by our house, only it was n't a house any more.'' She said <PERSON> Zillik </PERSON>'s 3-year-old daughter could be heard crying from the ruins of the house but rescuers could not reach her. `` And the people left alive have such a hard time,'' Ms. <PERSON> Stepanian </PERSON> said. She and her mother have moved to the Armenian capital, <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, until <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION> housing can be built for them. They do n't expect that anytime soon. The earthquake measuring 6.9 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale killed at least 25,000 people and left 500,000 people homeless. A year after the earthquake, 20,000 people are still missing, according to the relief agency Search. The destruction was massive. The town of <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION> was leveled. <PERSON> Kirovakan </PERSON> and some 300 villages were shattered. In <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION> alone _ then <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>'s second-largest city with 235,000 people _ the quake destroyed 99 nine-story apartment buildings, 10 schools, and every factory, officials said. The Soviet leadership promised after the quake that <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION> and the other demolished communities would be rebuilt within two years.
