<HEAD>Reagan Fights Poindexter Subpoena</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 3 grafs new, recasting; picks up 4th graf pvs, The subpoena.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is trying to quash a subpoena for his notes and diaries by onetime national security adviser <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>, saying it encroaches on the office of the presidency. <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>, facing trial Jan. 22, contends that notes and diaries compiled by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will show the ex-president authorized the activities for which <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> has been accused of crimes. In a court filing Wednesday, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>'s subpoena was a `` broad-gauge discovery device masquerading as a trial subpoena'' and that it seeks a `` laundry list'' of documents on 67 different subjects. The subpoena raises constitutional concerns about the president's prerogative to `` maintain a purely personal and private record of his thoughts and reflections,'' said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s lawyers. `` Nothing could be closer to the core of the presidency and more private than the intimate and confidential communications by the president with himself,'' the lawyers argued. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> suggested in separate filings that President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> might become involved in the battle over the records from <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s presidency. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> suggested a review of a limited number of diary excerpts by <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Greene </PERSON>, who is handling the <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> case. `` Only then should the former president and, if appropriate, the incumbent president be forced to assert or waive executive privilege,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said in the court papers. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> urge