presentatives. <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> also denied as overly broad <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>'s request to issue subpoenas to a number of congressional committees, the office of <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> counsel and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. The judge did not disclose how many committees <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> wanted to subpoena. The judge said the only apparent basis for the proposed subpoenas to the members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is that they `` at one time or other met with <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>.'' North, a former <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> staff member, was involved in the secret Contra resupply network and the administration's arms sales to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. He was convicted of three felonies in the Iran-Contra affair and is appealing. <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> has said that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> `` formulated'' or tacitly approved `` the administration's position'' on matters for which <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> now faces trial. He has said his communications with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> included discussion of a White House chronology that falsely said no one in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government knew at the time that a 1985 shipment to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> contained Hawk missiles. Another subject <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> says he discussed with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is the administration's view of a proposed <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> resolution of inquiry into <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s secret Contra resupply network. <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> is accused of obstructing <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> by endorsing earlier denials that the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securi