<FIRST>r a PM-AMA-AIDS     12-07 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AMA-AIDS,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>AMA Supports AIDS Notification; Attacks Tobacco</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> policymakers have recommended that communities set up systems to find and notify unsuspecting sexual or needle-sharing partners of people infected with the AIDS virus. The <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delegates </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday also broadened its attack on drug abuse to include tobacco-related diseases. The delegates approved the AIDS notification policy by voice vote as part of a resolution that encourages state legislatures to establish laws for reporting and following up on serious communicable diseases including AIDS. The resolution says communities and prisons should have systems to notify people who are at risk of AIDS because they have sexual partners or share drug needles with infected people. Dr. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> said concern for patient privacy should be secondary in light of the number of AIDS deaths in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. As of the end of October, the federal health authorities had recorded 112,241 cases of AIDS in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, with 66,493 deaths. However, former military physician <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> protested, saying devising a system to keep track of sexual or drug-use partners would `` waste incredible amounts of money'' and drive people infected with the AIDS virus underground. In other business, the association resisted an attempt to remove tobacco from a resolution naming substance abuse its top health priority. The resolution included the endorsement of a routine screening program for all pregnant women and those of childbearing age for evidence of substance abuse. Before ending its three-day meeting Wednesday, the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> delegates also ordered the restructuring of the group's internal organization and restricted the authority of its executive vice president. That action came after <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> Executive Vice President <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sammons </PERSON> approved two financial deals with executives that failed and caused thousands of dollars in losses. <PERSON> Sammons </PERSON> accepted full responsibility for the deals and a call for his immediate resignation failed, with more than two-thirds of the 435 delegates supporting him. <PERSON> Sammons </PERSON> is due to retire at the end of next year. The organization's 280,000 members account for about half the doctors in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
