<FIRST>r w PM-Cholesterol     12-07 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cholesterol,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Cholesterol Program Faulted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government's massive cholesterol education program places too much emphasis on drug treatments that may do more harm than good, a congressional panel was told today. But a federal official defended the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cholesterol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION>, saying its guidelines will improve the health of Americans and reduce the risk of heart attacks _ the nation's leading killer <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, an investigative reporter whose article in the September issue of The <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> magazine inflamed the controversy over cholesterol monitoring, said he questions the value of what he says is aggressive treatment recommended by the federal program. `` This is a very serious and expensive mistake in public policy,'' he told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on health. The program's cholesterol guidelines recommend diet as the treatment of choice, but says that failing that, patients with high levels of cholesterol should seek treatment with drugs. An estimated 60 million Americans are believed to have high blood cholesterol, a fatty substance that can clog arteries and contribute to heart disease and heart attacks. Besides cholesterol, other factors that have been identified as factors in heart disease are high blood pressure, obesity, smoking and lack of exercise. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said he agrees with advice in the program's guidelines that Americans should have their cholesterol levels checked and make their diets healthier by eating less fat, fewer calories and more fiber. He also said there is evidence that high cholesterol levels in middle-aged men makes them more vulnerable to heart disease, although he said the evidence of a link is much weaker for men over 65 and women of all ages who have no history of heart disease. `` But the central question is do we have effective medical treatment that justifies putting 60 million people under long-term care of their doctor,'' <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said. He said the evidence he has found shows that diet does little to lower cholesterol levels in the blood, and that while drug treatments show more benefit, they have not demonstrated significant ability to ward off fatal heart attacks. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said his complaint with the cholesterol program of the National Heart, Lung and <ORGANIZATION> Blood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> is that with evidence that diet is n't a significant factor in lowering cholesterol levels, many who follow the program's guidelines will turn to drug treatments that can have side effects including liver damage, cataracts and digestive difficulties. `` When people become frustrated with diet, there will be an expansion of drug treatment beyond what the architects of the program expected,'' he said. <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenfant </PERSON>, director of the Heart, Lung and <ORGANIZATION> Blood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, part of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, disputed <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> and said clinical trials have shown that lowering cholesterol levels by diet or drugs decreases the incidence of heart disease. `` Most people with high blood cholesterol will be able to lower their levels with diet alone, and only a small minority will have to resort to drugs,'' he said. <PERSON> Lenfant </PERSON> also noted that when the first Surgeon General's Report on Smoking and Health was released in the mid 1960s, critics started talking about the `` tobacco myth.'' `` It has taken a long time for the ripples to subside and for near unanimity to emerge that the risks of smoking are no myth,'' he said. `` Much the same is true for cholesterol. It may take a while before there is universal agreement about cholesterol-lowering, but cholesterol is also no myth.''
</TEXT>
