 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> praised savings and loan regulator <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> in a letter released Thursday, but a prominent Republican senator criticized the administration for not defending <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> who announced his resignation Monday under fire. While <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> saluted Wall for `` unselfish recognition'' that he could best help the industry by quitting, Sen. <PERSON> Jake </PERSON> <PERSON> Garn </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, the senior <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, accused the administration of `` not having any guts'' and failing to support the regulator. Wall was a focus of six weeks of hearings by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which was investigating his handling of the failure of <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Irvine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> is expected to be the nation's biggest thrift failure at a cost to taxpayers of $ 2 billion `` I am disappointed'' in the administration's dealing with Wall, <PERSON> Garn </PERSON> said in an interview with the <ORGANIZATION> Deseret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>. `` If it had been their nominee, their appointment, they would'' have supported Wall, who earlier served 12 years as the senator's top aide, he said. <PERSON> Garn </PERSON> said, `` <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> was a <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> appointee and they certainly in no way came to his defense.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, in a `` Dear Danny'' letter dated Wednesday, commended Wall for hard work as director of the Office of Thrift Supervision and for his `` unselfish recognition that the job of revitalizing the industry demands the complete and undistracted attention of the agency's entire leadership and staff.'' Calls for Wall's resignation had come from <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>; Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>; several major newspapers and citizens groups. White House Counsel <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyden </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> was also reported to be seeking his oustr, and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> failed to come to his defense in public. Wall took over as chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> in July 1987. In August of this year, he became director of the thrift office when the bank board was dismantled under <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L bailout legislation. He told a news conference he was resigning because continuing the fight with the committee would distract the agency from conducting its work. He is continuing to serve as thrift office director for an unspecified transitional period.
