<HEAD>Guerrillas Renew Attacks on Several San Salvador Neighborhoods</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with new attacks. Changes byline. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCOS ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leftist guerrillas renewed their assault on the Salvadoran capital today, setting up positions in at least seven neighborhoods and battling government soldiers. The rebels claimed they shot down a military helicopter, but the government said it suffered a mechanical problem and crashed. A statement by the armed forces press office said columns of rebels infiltrated the metropolitan area from the north, east and west during the night, including the upper-class <PERSON> Escalon </PERSON> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Benito </LOCATION> districts. There were no immediate reports of casualties, a military spokesman said, speaking on condition of anonymity for security reasons. Planes and helicopter gunships flew over the city during the night, dropping flares and strafing suspected rebel positions, while troops on the ground opened up with automatic weapons fire. But the new outbreak was much smaller than the fighting that began when guerrillas launched an urban offensive on Nov. 11 as part of their decade-old struggle for power against a succession of U.S.-backed governments. Fighting had subsided to a few scarce shots since Friday after the rebels withdrew from an incursion in <LOCATION> Escalon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Benito </LOCATION>. Also reported under attack were the working-class neighborhoods of Aytuxtepeque, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ramon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soyapango </LOCATION>, north and east of the city, and the small town of <LOCATION> Apopa </LOCATION>, to the north, the military said. The military spokesman said a U.S.-made helicopter crashed during the night because `` of mechanical failure,'' but the rebels' clandestine <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Venceremos </ORGANIZATION> claimed it was shot down by guerrilla fire In the broadcast, the guerrillas of the <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> also announced they were renewing their sabotage campaign against electric power installations and other economic targets. Rebel groups destroyed two city buses, and five private automobiles were destroyed by guerrillas in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ana </LOCATION>, 25 miles west of the capital, and a burlap bag factory in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Miguel </LOCATION>, 85 miles east of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. The rebels also were reported to have dynamited a bridge on the Litoral Highway near the city of <LOCATION> Usulutan </LOCATION>, 70 miles east of the capital. In an unrelated development, the government allowed three <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Episcopalian bishops to enter the country to check on several Episcopalians who were imprisoned during the recent offensive by leftist guerrillas. Bishops <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Frey </PERSON> of the diocese of <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Swing </PERSON> of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> arrived Wednesday on a commercial flight from <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and went through immigration proceedings with no problems. The first two had come on Tuesday and were told by immigration authorities their visas were invalid. They were put on a flight back to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, where they spent the night before making the second attempt to enter. <PERSON> Frey </PERSON> said President <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> sent a letter by telefax apologizing for the previous day's problems.
