<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is voicing deep skepticism about <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s efforts to repair the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s ailing economy, saying his ideas are simplistic and `` just far from the real world.'' The gloomy assessment arises from <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s weekend talks with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> during a two-day summit off the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> island of <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>. A senior administration official, intimately acquainted with the two leaders' discussions, said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> demonstrated he has `` less than a realistic economic notion of how to deal with his economic problems.'' Referring to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s ideas, the official said, `` They're simplistic. The official discussed the summit with a small group of reporters at the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> under assurances of remaining anonymous. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, speaking with reporters today aboard <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> One as <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> flew to <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, said, `` We would n't use that word.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said that the Soviets do have `` a lack of knowledge about how free enterprise systems work and how market economies work. And that was reflected in the conversation'' between <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> at <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>. He said `` simplistic'' was `` not a very good word to use. But there is going to be a problem in introducing free market economies to these -LRB- Marxist -RRB- countries.'' The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is suffering from widespread shortages of food, fuel and consumer goods despite <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERS