bserver status at a world organization that sets international trading rules, the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. Until now, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had strongly opposed Soviet participation. `` I think he needs a lot more sophistiction,'' the official said about <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. `` One of the things that will help him get the sophistication is something like observer status at <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION>, so he can have a look at how the world economy really works. `` I'm not sure where he wants to go with economic reforms,'' the official added. While welcoming <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s economic package, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> `` was not at all in a posture of saying, ` We want your help,''' the official said. `` What they do n't want is the notion that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is going to come in to bail them out. We're not going to do it, anyway.'' On another subject, the official said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> suggested some flexibility toward ethnic unrest in the Baltic states. The official said the Soviet leader said he was prepared `` to look on all kinds of autonomy,'' but that he would `` draw the line at independence.'' The official quoted <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> as saying, `` ` We need to look for new structures to meet new circumstances.''' The official added, `` He seemed quite open to experimentation.''
