<HEAD>Villagers Want to Sell Their Statue of Stalin</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MORT ROSENBLUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KOMAROV, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A banner on the outskirts says, `` With Soviet Union Forever,'' but the people of this <LOCATION> Bohemian </LOCATION> village want to sell their 20-foot statue of <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> for Western currency. `` Everyone in town is with the revolution against the Communists except one guy, and he's in the secret police,'' said butcher <PERSON> Vaclav </PERSON> <PERSON> Jicha </PERSON>. `` Well, maybe 10 percent of <PERSON> Komarov </PERSON> opposes these changes, but all of the rest are happy,'' said elementary school teacher, <PERSON> Jiri </PERSON> <PERSON> Beran </PERSON>. Whatever the numbers, a glance outside <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> shows that the students' November revolution is firmly implanted in smaller cities and rural areas. In <LOCATION> Plzen </LOCATION>, an industrial city 50 miles west of <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, anti-Communist posters are less evident than in the capital. But attitudes are clear. During last week's strike, even the fabled Urquell Pilsener beer stopped flowing. `` No one hesitated when we asked them to stop,'' said <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kylbergr </PERSON>, strike organizer at Prazdroj Brewery. Workers left even before he got a chance to read his manifesto. `` We wo n't have to disband Communist groups here,'' added <PERSON> Kylbergr </PERSON>, 27. `` They'll destroy themselves.'' If any place in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> exemplifies the new mood, it is <PERSON> Komarov </PERSON>, a village of 2,200 people about 30 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Komarov </PERSON> makes machine parts _ no one likes to be more specific _ and the factory put up an immense stone statue of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> in the 1950s. It's still there on the square, one of the last Stalin monuments left in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Reformers were about to smash it into gravel when a visiting professor mentioned someone in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> collected <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> memorabilia. <PERSON> Komarov </PERSON> townsfolk, in need of an old-age home, figured <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> might be of some use to them after all. That was a few days ago. The plan, in its earliest stages, has not yet reached the proper channels for approval. At first glance, <PERSON> Komarov </PERSON> looks like a party town. Walls are festooned with red stars, the odd hammer and sickle, and standard-issue Marxist-Leninist poster art. A bulletin board announced a party youth march. And there was <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s statue, identifying him as, `` The Greater Teacher of Working People, Liberator of our Country.'' Asked about it, <PERSON> Beran </PERSON> advised: `` Do n't pay any attention to that garbage. Look over there.'' He pointed to glass double doors to the little shopping mall, plastered with leaflets from the opposition Civic Forum. Inside, in a well-stocked store offering everything from bidets to bicycles, saleswoman <PERSON> Iva </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartipanova </PERSON> explained how the pamphlets got there. `` We did n't know anything about what was happening in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> until these things appeared on the doors,'' she said. `` During the night, someone ripped them off. But then they appeared again.'' When demonstrations began in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, volunteer taxi drivers took students and actors from town to town to spread the word. They found willing ears in <PERSON> Komarov </PERSON>. `` Anyone who lived through the 1968 invasion must support what the Civic Forum is doing,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Bartipanova </PERSON> said. In 1968, she was just bringing her infant son home from the hospital when she ran into Soviet troops headquartered just up the road. Down a country road from <PERSON> Komarov </PERSON>, <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Prochazka </PERSON>, 65, lives alone on isolated farm the state decided to return to him last year after keeping it for four decades. He knows all about the uprising. <PERSON> Prochazka </PERSON> could hardly believe it. Back in the 1950s, he watched the Communist militia shoot two men who mocked the idea of collective farms. He spent years in a forced labor camp because his father would not join a collective. He suffered later when a nephew defected. Now he makes a meager living sawing logs in the farm's small mill, which the state still owns. Despite it all, he has swung right back into political kibitzing, in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s democratic tradition. `` The opposition is doing the wrong thing,'' he said. `` We need two strong parties, the <ORGANIZATION> Peoples </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the Socialists.'' In sharp contrast to the immediate past, almost everyone was happy to talk. Mothers pushing babies in prams carefully spelled out their names. Young soldiers described their enthusiasm, and their officers' misgivings. For <PERSON> Frantisek </PERSON> <PERSON> Sojka </PERSON>, a 85-year-old pensioner in a moth-eaten fur hat, the biggest surprise of the revolution was seeing an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> reporter and English photographer wandering around loose. <PERSON> Sojka </PERSON> would just as soon keep the <LOCATION> Stalin </LOCATION> statue _ it is art, he says, _ but he wants to see it accompanied by a monument to <PERSON> Tomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Masaryk </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s first president.
