<HEAD>Prime Minister Visits Sikh Temple in Campaign to End Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DEL2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister V.P. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> visited <LOCATION> Sikhism </LOCATION>'s holiest shrine, the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION>, on Thursday in a major initiative by his government to end the lingering secessionist campaign by Sikh militants. It was the first visit by a prime minister to the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> in more than five years, since shortly after a bloody army raid that led to the assassination of Prime Minister <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>. `` Too much bloodshed has taken place,'' the Hindu prime minister told about 20,000 Sikhs inside the 14th century shrine. `` The time has come to win the hearts of the people.'' In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>, a judge formally dropped charges against four Sikhs accused of participating in the Oct. 31, 1984, assassination of Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>. Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> was shot and killed by two Sikh bodyguards angered by the army attack she ordered on the Golden Temple in June 1984 to drive out <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> militants using it as a base. One assassin was shot and killed by security men. The other was convicted along with an accomplice and both were hanged in January. Conspiracy charges were later filed against four other Sikhs. Last week, the government said it would withdraw the charges in a conciliatory move toward the Sikh community. `` One does wonder why the move was not made earlier,'' said Judge <PERSON> Jaspal </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, himself a Sikh, in ordering the charges dropped. All Sikhs and many Hindus use the name <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, which means lion. Two of the Sikhs accused of conspiracy were elected to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> in last month's general elections, in which V.P. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> and his <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> coalition </ORGANIZATION> prevented <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>, Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s son and successor, from returning to power. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> was sworn in as prime minister Saturday and said solving the Sikh dispute in the northern state of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> would be one of his top priorities. On Wednesday, he made an effort to heal rifts between Hindus and Moslems by by appointing a Moslem, <PERSON> Mufti </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Sayeed </PERSON>, to the key job of minister of home affairs. Religious riots this fall left at least 300 people dead. His visit to the Golden Temple was noticeable for the almost total lack of bodyguards, who surrounded <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> during his public appearances. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> traveled in an open jeep from <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Raja </PERSON> <PERSON> Sansi </PERSON> airport to the temple after refusing to sit in a bulletproof sedan. `` Your love to me is my security,'' the prime minister told the gathering at the gold-domed temple. `` I have not come here for any political or governmental purposes. I have come to perform prayers in the holy shrine so that peace and normalcy can be restored.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> was the last prime minister to visit the temple. She came a week after the army raid. The Sikh secessionist campaign was launched by a small group of radicals in 1982 and exacerbated by the raid on the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> and by anti-Sikh riots in northern <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> after Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s assassination At least 1,200 people died in the army raid, and the temple suffered heavy damage, turning even moderate Sikhs against the government. At least 3,000 Sikhs were killed in ensuing riots. Sikhs, easily identifiable by the their long hair, flowing beards and colorful turbans, form only 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 880 million people but are a majority in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. Sikh militants say their community is discriminated against by the Hindus, who make up about 80 percent of the population. Officials say at least 7,500 people have been killed in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> since the Sikh campaign began. <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> Governor <PERSON> Sidhartha </PERSON> <PERSON> Shankar </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> resigned Thursday and was replaced by <PERSON> Nirmal </PERSON> <PERSON> Kumar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mukarji </PERSON>, an appointee of the new government. The state is ruled by the federal government in the absence of an elected legislative assembly, and the governor is the top administrator.
