<HEAD>North Dakota Government in Uproar After Special Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Turnout was...', to ADD that it was highest
for such election on record; SUBS 17th graf, `It's way...', to CORRECT
that governor's term expires at end of 1992, sted 1993.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALE WETZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Reeling from voters' overwhelming rejection of three tax increases, the governor is proposing $ 98 million in budget cuts that could signal major changes for his economically strapped state. `` It's difficult to get people to look at the complexity of an issue like this,'' Democratic Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinner </PERSON> said Wednesday. `` I tried hard. But I do n't think I achieved the message. I really do n't.'' He spent weeks campaigning on behalf of higher state income, sales and gasoline taxes, a year after he easily won re-election against a Republican opponent who ran on an anti-tax platform. But <PERSON> North </PERSON> <PERSON> Dakotans </PERSON> thronged to the polls Tuesday to defeat those tax measures as well as five other issues proposing mandatory seat belts, video gambling, sex education for schools, legislative pensions and the reorganization of state government. `` People were in the mood to vote no, and once they started voting no, they just kept going,'' said former state <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Tish </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>. Turnout was unofficially counted at 253,429, or 53 percent of the state's estimated voting population, a record turnout for a special election. Of the three defeated tax measures, a proposal to raise the state sales tax from 5 percent to 6 percent fared best. It lost by 53-47 percent. Increases in income and gasoline taxes were rejected by 60-40 percent. Sinner's proposed cuts, which are subject to legislative approval, would hit public schools hardest. Elementary and secondary education would lose $ 34 million, according to state <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> documents. The state's higher education system faces a possible $ 24 million cut and state human services a $ 21 million reduction. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>'s general fund budget totals $ 1.12 billion during the current two-year budgeting period, which ends June 30, 1991. Sinner may call lawmakers into special session early next year, but he plans to consult legislative leaders before making his decision. The state is celebrating its centennial year, but its past decade has been bittersweet. The economy relies heavily on farming and energy production and has suffered from drought and low prices for oil and wheat. North Dakota farmers got more than $ 400 million in drought aid last year. The latest campaign was the governor's second in three years to raise taxes. In 1987, he took a leading role in persuading voters to endorse an income tax increase, which was approved while the Legislature was in session. But Wednesday, he said his latest effort may have been a waste. `` It's easy to see why this budget is so extremely tight, and yet the people never really seem to perceive that,'' Sinner said. He contended tax increases are needed to maintain existing services. Sinner, who has talked of running for a third term, shrugged off questions about the political damage from his tax campaign. `` It's way too early for me to think about that,'' said <PERSON> Sinner </PERSON>, whose four-year term ends at the end of 1992. He added, `` I did n't take the job because I wanted to perpetuate myself in office. Opponents of the tax increases said the governor has failed to pare spending enough, and that farmers and businesses can not afford a heavier tax burden. `` Governor Sinner needs to put more of his energy into economic development,'' said <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> <PERSON> French </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Bismarck </LOCATION> businessman who led opposition to the taxes. `` Instead, he's spent his time trying to raise taxes.'' Legislators sensed anger in the vote. `` There seems to be a bitterness,'' said Democratic state Sen. <PERSON> Geraldine </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON>. `` <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> people are short of money and hurting, and to me -LRB- the election -RRB- was almost a striking out.'' Voters have had it with taxes and government, said Sen. <PERSON> Bryce </PERSON> <PERSON> Streibel </PERSON>, a Republican. `` Government is no longer a servant of the people,'' he said. `` It's become a monster.''
