<HEAD>Taxpayers Pay Insurance for Lawmakers Considering Reforms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A safe driving record and living in a low-crime area are two ways to get lower auto insurance rates, but being elected to the Legislature might be more effective. <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> are the only two states that reimburse legislators for the lease and insurance on their cars. A vote on a compromise insurance reform bill is expected next week in the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> Legislature, where the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in June voted down a proposal that would have cut rates by about 25 percent. <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>'s rates are among the highest in the nation, fueled in part, The <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inquirer </ORGANIZATION> said, by legislation that was drafted by lobbyists for the insurance industry and trial lawyers, who benefit from personal-injury lawsuits. Two state senators are not reimbursed for car insurance. One does n't have a driver's license or car and the other is Sen. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenwood </PERSON>. All 48 other senators have the taxpayers cover most of their insurance premiums. `` I think to the extent that every time my insurance goes up I feel the pain too _ that makes me like the people I represent,'' <PERSON> Greenwood </PERSON> said. Sen. <PERSON> Chakka </PERSON> <PERSON> Fattah </PERSON>, who paid $ 184 to insure his 1989 <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> last year, said it is unfair to say that legislators do n't care about the insurance issue because their car insurance is paid by the state. `` That's just like saying because we have jobs we would n't be concerned about unemployment,'' <PERSON> Fattah </PERSON> said. State Insurance Commissioner <PERSON> Constance </PERSON> <PERSON> B </PERSON>. <PERSON> Foster </PERSON> said the state's reimbursement policy could make it more difficult for legislators to adopt reform legislation. `` If a person is isolated from the problem, it's very easy to minimize it _ even if they have teen-age sons and daughters,'' she said. Foster was one of the key proponents of the insurance-reform bill defeated by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in June. Foster has the use of a state-owned and - insured 1989 Buick Century State records show that many <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> lawmakers lease late-model Cadillacs, Lincolns and other luxury cars. The insurance on those cars runs from several hundred dollars a year for rural legislators to thousands for <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> lawmakers. Under House rules, representatives can be reimbursed for up to 100 percent for their car insurance. Senators can be reimbursed up to 95 percent. Many legislators said that such a benefit is normal in business and that it helps them perform their jobs better. They also disputed that the practice insulates them from the high cost of insurance because they still have to pay for insurance on personal and family cars.
