<HEAD>Scandal Figure Vows to Fight Extradition, Says Fair Trial Unlikely</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A jailed East German official accused of embezzling will fight extradition back to the Communist country, saying the growing turmoil makes a fair trial unlikely, his lawyer said Thursday. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Schalck-Golodkowski </PERSON> fled the country after prosecutors disclosed he was operating a weapons ring selling arms to countries in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. The growing scandal already has led to one suicide and the arrest of <PERSON> Schalck-Golodkowski </PERSON>'s deputy for allegedly taking $ 110 million in West German marks out of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Such allegations are particularly embarrassing for <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, which for years has claimed that it needs more Western currency to support its economy. <PERSON> Schalck-Golodkowski </PERSON> had supervised the various government-owned businesses that brought in the badly needed Western money. He disappeared while on an official visit to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> on Saturday, quickly becoming the target of an international manhunt that added even more damaging publicity to the deeply troubled nation. <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION>, a small party that recently broke with the Communists, said the allegations made the country look like a `` banana republic.'' <PERSON> Schalck-Golodkowski </PERSON> turned himself in to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> authorities Wednesday night and immediately promised to repay $ 31 million to <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> from Swiss bank accounts. That is only a small part of what <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s official news media claim he embezzled. In an interview with a <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> TV station, the former official's lawyer, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Danckert </PERSON>, said his client would resist being returned to <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> for trial. <PERSON> Danckert </PERSON> said that `` the uncertainty that we have seen everywhere in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'' made a fair trial unlikely. The national frenzy aimed at punishing past corruption has led <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> officials to warn that calls for `` revenge against the guilty'' were sparking widespread fears. <PERSON> Danckert </PERSON> said <PERSON> Schalck-Golodkowski </PERSON> would appeal to the West German <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> if necessary to avoid an extradition. On Thursday, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> prosecutor <PERSON> Dietrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON> said <PERSON> Schalck-Golodkowski </PERSON> would stay in jail indefinitely and that the former East German official `` feels that he is not guilty.'' The <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> prosecutor added that an extradition to <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> is still possible based on the Communist nation's arrest warrant for embezzlement. The charge carries a maximum of 10 years in prison. However, <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON> said his office had not turned over anyone to <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> for prosecution in 20 years and that it was possible he would be set free. <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON> said that <PERSON> Schalck-Golodkowski </PERSON> could be tried on the allegations in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, if the East Germans can prove he committed the crimes. On Wednesday, the official East German news agency <ORGANIZATION> ADN </ORGANIZATION> reported the suicide of an official caught two days earlier trying to leave a government building with two suitcases stuffed with East German and West German money. ADN did not give his name, but said he was connected to the <PERSON> Schalck-Golodkowski </PERSON> case. <PERSON> Manfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Seidel </PERSON>, who served as <PERSON> Schalck-Golodkowski </PERSON>'s deputy, was arrested on suspicion of having smuggled $ 110 million in West Germank marks out of the country.
