<HEAD>Ceremonies Commemorate Pearl Harbor Anniversary</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with detail from ceremonies. Picks
up penultimate graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEARL HARBOR, Hawaii (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A thousand people gathered at two sites today to remember the `` day of infamy'' that killed more than 2,000 servicemen and brought the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> into World War II. Ceremonies on the 48th anniversary of the Dec. 7, 1941, Japanese attack on <LOCATION> Pearl </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> included a moment of silence and a 21-gun salute. Simultaneous ceremonies were held by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> aboard the aboard the USS Arizona Memorial, where about 100 guests attended, and onshore at the <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> Memorial Visitors Center. The shore ceremony, open to the public and sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, which runs the center, attracted about 900 people. Adm. <PERSON> Huntington </PERSON> <PERSON> Hardisty </PERSON>, commander of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>, spoke at the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ceremony, alluding to the new peace initiatives between the East and West blocs. `` As the opportunity arises to reduce tensions and the potential for open conflict, we should seize it and support it,'' he said. But he said Americans also `` must continue to speak out'' against perceived threats to the nation's security. The speaker at the public ceremony was retired Rear Adm. <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Dybdal </PERSON>, who was a gunnery officer aboard the USS Helm during the attack. In all, 19 ships were sunk or damaged and some 2,300 men died on the day President <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> said would `` live in infamy.'' The sunken <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> is the final resting place for 1,102 <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> men and Marines. The memorial spans the hull of the Ariozona battleship, which still flies the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flag. It is the only <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ship not in commission that is allowed to do so.
