<SECOND>AM-Human Rights Killings,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>68 Human Rights Monitors Killed in Last Year, Group Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sixty-eight human rights monitors were killed worldwide in the last year, double the number in the previous 12 months, an international human rights monitoring organization said Thursday. <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Watch </ORGANIZATION> said 63 of the killings were in countries usually considered to be democratic, but added in its annual report that `` the danger in democratic countries ... is, of course, not an argument in favor of dictatorships of the right or of the left.'' The organization said it had little or no information on persecutions of human rights monitors in <LOCATION> Albania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> because it is virtually impossible for citizens in those countries to monitor government activities. Nevertheless, the report said, `` the dangers that attend efforts to monitor and defend human rights in some ` democracies' should give pause to those who have celebrated the democratic tide that has swept across the world in the 1980s.'' `` At least in a number of Latin American and East Asian countries, the advent of electoral democracy has not meant great advances in respect for human rights.'' `` It is when a certain degree of openness prevails but when the rule of law has not been established that the perils are greatest,'' the organization said. In <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, where the group said a history of human rights violations has been exacerbated by the violence associated with the drug trade, 24 human rights monitors were killed, more than in any other country. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> was second with 14 and `` many of the cases reflect the intense struggle over land distribution in rural areas,'' Human Rights Watch said. The 345-page report discussed 1,200 cases of persecution of human rights monitors in 72 countries, including arrest, imprisonment and torture of people who gather and disseminate information on their own governments' human rights abuses. <PERSON> Aryeh </PERSON> <PERSON> Neier </PERSON>, executive director of <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Watch </ORGANIZATION>, said <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, where a new reformist government has come to power, was second only to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in the total number of cases. But he said many of those listed had been released about two weeks before the report was issued. `` Not all the people we care about in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> have yet been released, so there is a way to go,'' <PERSON> Neier </PERSON> added. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> takes up 36 pages in the report and <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> 23. The report devoted only six pages to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, but said some of the thousands arrested after the June 3-4 disturbances in Tiananmen Square were known to have been signers of statements and petitions on human rights issues. In addition to the 68 killings, 10 more human rights monitors `` disappeared'' after being taken into custody, the organization said. Human Rights Watch is made up of five regional committees: <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Watch </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Americas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Watch </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> Watch, <ORGANIZATION> Helsinki </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Watch </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Watch </LOCATION>. It is headquartered in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>.
