<SECOND>AM-S&amp;L Rules,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stricter Standards Take Effect</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Keating Money, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Strict new financial standards effective Thursday will force more than a third of the nation's savings institutions to shrink or shut down if they ca n't raise new capital. Only 1,800 of 2,900 S & amp; Ls have enough capital to satisfy the requirement, prompting industry analysts to nickname the deadline `` Pearl Harbor Day'' because it coincides with the 48th anniversary of the Japanese attack on <LOCATION> Pearl </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>. `` It's a good analogy, except in one respect,'' said economist <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Litan </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Brookings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> think tank. `` This was n't a sneak attack. -LRB- S & amp; Ls -RRB- should have known this was coming a long time ago.'' The new rules were required under <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L bailout legislation enacted Aug. 9 and are considered the cornerstone reform of the bill. The Office of Thrift Supervision published them Nov. 6. Advocates of forcing S & amp; L owners to back their lending with more of their own money say the measure will encourage institutions to avoid risky investments that could run up big losses for the government deposit insurance fund. Of the 1,100 institutions falling short of the standard, about 300 are already insolvent and due to be transferred to the <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> for liquidation. Of the 800 remaining, about 270 likely will be able to shrink or raise capital on their own and about 230 likely wo n't be able to do it before mandatory growth restrictions take effect on Jan. 1, 1991, <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON>, director of the thrift office, said Thursday. `` Then 300 in the middle are candidates for the matchmaker program, blind dates, arranged marriages, however you want to put it,'' <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accountants </ORGANIZATION> Thursday in a reference to a thrift office program aimed at matching weak S & amp; Ls with merger partners. Private analysts, however, are skeptical about the prospects for capital-deficient institutions. `` There are very good reasons to question whether the guys in the middle will survive, certainly in their present form,'' <PERSON> Litan </PERSON> said. `` ` The most likely strategy will be shrinkage because they will not be successful in attracting new capital. There's a pall hanging over the entire thrift industry, which makes investors nervous.'' Anticipating the rules, <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls have been shrinking, shedding a record $ 15.2 billion in assets in September and $ 13.3 billion in August, according to the latest report available. <PERSON> Litan </PERSON> and another economist, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Getman </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Wefa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in <PERSON> Bala </PERSON> <PERSON> Cynwyd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, said another provision in the thrift bill requiring S & amp; Ls to concentrate 70 percent of their assets on housing loans, up from 60 percent, is discouraging investors and virtually forcing the shrinkage. `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is saying to thrifts, ` Put all your eggs in one basket,' and that basket is looking real shaky,'' <PERSON> Getman </PERSON> said, noting weakening real estate markets in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> on top of already soft markets in the <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION>. `` This is setting up the industry for what will be a knockout punch in the early 1990s,'' he said, predicting that the Southeast will be the next region with real estate problems. `` The right analogy to draw for these 800 thrifts is they are like prisoners on death row. They have another 15 years to live,'' <PERSON> Getman </PERSON> said.
