<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has bought 410,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat at subsidized prices for delivery in 1989-90, the seventh year of a long-term grain supply agreement, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. F. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickerson </PERSON>, general sales manager for the department's <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said shipments are scheduled in January and February The wheat was sold under the department's Export Enhancement Program, or <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION>, which provides subsidies to exporters selling <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commodities to designated foreign markets. <PERSON> Dickerson </PERSON> said only 14,200 tons of wheat remain in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s current <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION> allocation of 1.5 million tons announced May 2. It was the second <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat sale since the seventh year of the long-term grain agreement began Oct. 1, although more than 10.3 million tons of corn have been sold for 1989-90 delivery, along with soybeans and soybean meal. A sale of 215,000 tons was reported on Monday. The pact runs through Dec. 31, 1990, and a new agreement is currently being negotiated. In 1988-89, the sixth year of the current agreement, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> bought about 5.4 million tons of wheat and more than 16.3 million tons of corn, plus soybeans, soybean meal and grain sorghums. A metric ton is 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels of wheat. The 410,000 tons are equal to more than 15 million bushels worth around $ 57 million at recent <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm prices. <PERSON> Dickerson </PERSON> reported the subsidies at an average of $ 16.81 per ton, or about 46 cents per bushel. The <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION> arrangement allows private exporters to sell wheat and other designated commodities to specified countries at reduced prices to meet foreign competition. The exporters then collect free government surpluses of grain or other products as bonuses, or subsidies. <PERSON> Dickerson </PERSON> said the wheat was sold by <ORGANIZATION> Alfred </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Toepfer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, 150,000 tons; <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dreyfus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 135,000; <ORGANIZATION> Cargill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, 50,000; <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, 25,000; <ORGANIZATION> J. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, 25,000; and <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 25,000. Since <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION> began in 1985, more than $ 2.6 billion in subsidies have been paid to exporters to ship a variety of commodities to overseas customers. As of Nov. 30, sales totaled 87.2 million tons of grain, including 64.4 million tons of wheat. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, the largest <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION> beneficiary, has bought more than 17.5 million tons of wheat. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is second at 13.2 million tons of wheat, plus 185 head of cattle.
