<DATELINE>PEARL HARBOR, Hawaii (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> should seize and support opportunities to reduce international tensions, the commander of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> said Thursday in commemorating the 48th anniversary of the <LOCATION> Pearl </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> attack. `` But when we perceive a threat against the interests and security of the nation, we must continue to speak out, even if the tide of public opinion is running the other way,'' said Adm. <PERSON> Huntington </PERSON> <PERSON> Hardisty </PERSON> during a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ceremony aboard the USS Arizona Memorial. Hardisty noted that an 18-year-old sailor lost in the Dec. 7, 1941, attack by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> would now be 66. That sailor would be pleased to see that the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> command is waging peace, <PERSON> Hardisty </PERSON> told about 100 invited guests. `` He would be pleased to see that our nation's security posture in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> is in good shape,'' Hardisty said. `` But I also think the sailor would sound a warning that peace requires strong, credible forces, and constant vigilence.'' A minute of silence was observed at 7:55 a.m., the time the air raid began. The minute ended with a flyover by <ORGANIZATION> Hawaii </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> jets in the `` missing man'' formation. Representatives of veterans, civic and patriotic organizations presented wreaths during the ceremony, which also included prayers and a 21-gun salute. Among those attending were <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Reps. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Akaka </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Hawaii </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Lancaster </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.C. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Leath </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PE