<SECOND>AM-Aspin-Defense Cuts,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aspin Warns Parochial Interests May Form Defense Budget</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pentagon-Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> chairman charged Thursday that the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration bungled the announcement of future cuts in defense spending by failing to spell out a military strategy. Rep. <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON>, D-Wis., said <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> directed the services to come up with ways to slash $ 180 billion from <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spending during fiscal 1992 to fiscal 1994 but provided no policy guidance Without a strategy, the administration faces the likelihood of the defense budget being crafted by lawmakers concerned with parochial interests instead of by the administration, <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> said. `` In the last couple of weeks the administration has fumbled the defense budget ball big time,'' <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> said in a speech to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> Democrat said `` the budget exercise asked the services where they would cut. It did n't tell them what threats to assume, what roles to emphasize or what missions to minimize.'' Complicating the situation was <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON>'s decision to discuss the cuts in published reports and television interviews, <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> said. The cuts, according to the lawmaker, will come from unrealistic budget totals envisioned by the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> and in the long run will amount to substantial, but no massive, reductions. `` If we compare it to the five-year defense plan that they are now working with in the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, a cut of $ 180 billion in 1992, 1993 and 1994 would mean a reduction of about 4.5 percent per year in each of those years. That's in real terms, after accounting for inflation,'' <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> said. The problems stemming from the administration's handling of the issue will be worse if it falters in producing a strategy for the budget cuts, <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> said. `` When your defense budget is not supported by a military strategy, it will be patched together with a pork strategy,'' <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> said. `` Of course, even if you have a military strategy it is hard to fend off a pork strategy, but if you have no military strategy, you have no chance.'' <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> said the administration faces allegations that it will be fashioning a strategy to fit the budget. Nevertheless, the administration must reopen the debate over Soviet military capabilities and intentions in a time of fast-moving events in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The administration then must outline a strategy to ensure that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> gets the most for its reduced defense dollars, <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> said.
