<SECOND>AM-Germany-Protest,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germans Rally Against Communists, Secret Police</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 2,500 East Germans marched through the city center late Thursday shouting slogans against the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the country's once-feared secret police. Hundreds of the demonstators blew shrill, ear-piercing whistles and shouted for the secret police to stop meddling in citizens' affairs `` Imprison the Communists!'' the marchers demanded, referring to disgraced former leaders accused of having misused their offices or made off with state funds during four decades of Communist rule in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The rally, which started at <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s sprawling Alexanderplatz, followed the broad <LOCATION> Marx-Engels-Forum </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Boulevard </LOCATION> and passed city hall, included demonstrators who hoisted signs calling for free elections next year. `` We Demand Quick Free Elections'' and `` The Communists Must Now Pay for the Mistakes of Misery,'' placards read. `` We Have Had Enough of Election Fraud.'' Former <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Egon </PERSON> <PERSON> Krenz </PERSON> was forced to resign from his posts as party leader and president this week following accusations that he allowed approval of falsified April election results. Two demonstrators carried a sign showing a caricature of a man shredding polling records. Another sign denounced <ORGANIZATION> Krenz </ORGANIZATION> and West German Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>, who has offered a plan for German reunification. `` We need neither <ORGANIZATION> Krenz </ORGANIZATION> nor <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> _ we'll only feel well when we govern ourselves,'' the sign read. There had been reports the demonstrators would march on the secret police headquarters in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, but the demonstrators never passed the building. About 200 demonstrators broke off from the main column at the Communist Party headquarters, where they shouted `` Come Out, Come Out, We Are Peaceful!'' Police presence as the march wound through the city was negligible. At one point, a policeman using the megaphone of a patrol car shouted, `` Attention, attention, this is the people's police, please use the sidewalks, you are disrupting traffic.'' The marchers ignored the order, booing and jeering. The police did nothing. People in a hotel along the route cheered on the marchers, who waved back. At about the same time, about 30 demonstrators from <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> pushed their way to the front of the column of marchers and shouted anti-Nazi slogans. Part of the procession marched by the Dietrich-Bonhoeffer building, where negotiations between the Communists, other recognized political parties and opposition groups were under way. The marchers joined a chorus of calls there for free elections and other democratic reforms in a Communist nation under siege by its own people. About 90 minutes later, the marchers dispersed peacefully.
