<HEAD>Garbage-Eating Pigs Trapped, Sent to Slaughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANFORD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The wild pig population feeding on garbage at the <LOCATION> Seminole </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> landfill had multiplied to about 1,500, and the county decided it was time to do something. Enter <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Godwin </PERSON>, 23-year-old professional trapper. He pays the county $ 52 apiece to round up the hogs and truck them away to sell to a slaughter house. `` People think catching hogs is fun, but it's a job,'' <PERSON> Godwin </PERSON> said Tuesday after several days of trapping and muscling squealing hogs _ which weighed up to 350 pounds _ into a truck. <PERSON> Godwin </PERSON> arrived at the 1,200-acre landfill early Saturday with three helpers and began their routine: Set traps by day, sleep in their vehicles at night while the hogs get trapped, and the next day haul the hogs to <LOCATION> Myakka </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, a three-hour drive. It's tough work, he said. `` They get mean. They ai n't no pets, you know. They'll catch you if you let them,'' <PERSON> Godwin </PERSON> said. Now landfill workers say they will miss the porkers. `` They have gotten used to seeing them run around out there. You look at the little ones, they're kind of cute,'' said <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Blakeley </PERSON>, the county's solid waste manager. `` But, you've got to do what you've got to do.''
