<HEAD>One Year After Quake, Armenians Mourn the Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf pvs `And the...' with one graf to CORRECT spelling
of first name of Stepanian; pickup graf 10 `The earthquake...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LENINAKAN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bells tolled, thousands wept in the graveyards and plaintive chants filled the streets Thursday as <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> marked the first anniversary of the earthquake that killed 25,000 of its people. In this mountain city, officials stopped the town clock forever at 11:41, the minute disaster struck, and held a moment of silence. Only muffled sobs broke the stillness. `` If only it could all have been a dream, and we could wake up and have everyone here again,'' Armenian poet <PERSON> Maro </PERSON> <PERSON> Marzarian </PERSON> told a crowd of several hundred gathered to dedicate a memorial to <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION>'s thousands of dead. In a snowy cemetery just outside of town, women sobbed at the gravesites, some of them caressing photographs etched on the tombstones and men stood stony eyed and silent. Many graves held unidentified corpses, with markers reading only `` 238, woman'' or `` 453, child.'' `` Your soul hurts so much you just ca n't express it,'' said <PERSON> Lilia </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepanian </PERSON>, 25, whose brother, <PERSON> Zillik </PERSON>, and his family were crushed to death in their <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION> apartment. `` You remember that on this day, at this time, they were already gone,'' she said. `` At this time one year ago I was standing by our house, only it was n't a house any more. She said <PERSON> Zillik </PERSON>'s 3-year-old daughter could be heard crying from the ruins of the house but rescuers could not get to her in time. <PERSON> Stepanian </PERSON>'s mother, <PERSON> Rima </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Zillik </PERSON>'s wife had been due to give birth to a second child three weeks later. `` And the people left alive have such a hard time,'' <PERSON> Lilia </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepanian </PERSON> said. She and her mother moved to Armenian capital of <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> until <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION> housing could be built for them _ which they do n't expect any time soon. The earthquake measuring 6.9 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale killed at least 25,000 people, left 20,000 missing and destroyed the homes of 500,000 more. In the nearby village of <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION>, where the quake destroyed virtually every house, residents dedicated a new church of galvanized steel. Standing above a hillside crowded with graves, it shone in the sun under Thursday's bright blue sky. Armenians stopped work Thursday to honor the dead, and Armenian TV broadcast a program on earthquake damage and reconstruction. After the quake rocked <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> with such devastating force, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> opened its borders to foreign assistance for the first time, accepting the help of thousands of experts, including rescue teams, doctors and construction specialists. More than a half-billion dollars in assistance poured into the disaster area from overseas, altering the course of East-West relations as generosity and mercy overcame years of Soviet propaganda depicting Westerners as greedy and hate-filled. <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> said Thursday that foreign assistance as of mid-October totaled $ 586 million. The most generous donors were <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> with $ 95 million; <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> with $ 84.5 million; the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> with $ 42 million; <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> with $ 38 million; <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> with $ 34.5 million; <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> with $ 30 million; and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> with $ 28 million. On Thursday, the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> announced Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> sent $ 100,000 to Armenian Christians, saying he wanted to give `` a new sign of his affection for those peoples and of his active participation in the difficult test they have been subjected to.'' <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> officials gave the gift to Vasken I, the chief leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Armenian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, which broke from the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in the 6th century but maintains good ties with the Holy See.
