<HEAD>Lunch Meat Recalled For Possible Food Poisoning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Sumter, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, processor is voluntarily recalling a single 240-pound shipment of luncheon meat distributed to nearby stores because some of the product may be contaminated by food poisoning bacteria, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. <ORGANIZATION> Harvin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Choice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Meats </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> sold the product _ `` <ORGANIZATION> Harvin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sliced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Luncheon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Meat </ORGANIZATION>'' packed in 6-ounce vacuum packages _ exclusively to grocery and convenience stores in a 20-mile radius of <LOCATION> Sumter </LOCATION>, officials said. The possible contamination involves Listeria monocytogenes, bacteria that can cause severe illness, said <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>, head of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inspection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. Consumers should return the packages where purchased. No other product of the company is involved in the recall. k <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> said no illnesses have been reported as a result of eating the suspected product. Cartons containing the packages carry the production code, 0318. And each carton and package bears a <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> inspection seal with `` Est. 6592'' inside the seal. Food contaminated with the bacteria can cause listeriosis, described as a rare but potentially serious disease, particularly for those with weakend immune systems _ infants, the elderly and the chronically ill. Symptoms are flu-like and include fever chills, headache, backache and sometimes abdominal pain and diarrhea. Consumers with questions about the recall can phone the toll