<HEAD>De Klerk Refuses Independent Prope of Death Squad Allegations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President F.W. <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON> said Friday he would not order an independent inquiry into allegations of police death squads because justice officials could do the job faster and just as well. Several police officers, serving and retired, will be investigated and five have requested suspension from duty until investigations or legal proceedings are completed, <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON> and <PERSON> Adriaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON>, the law and order minister, said in statements released at 12:01 a.m. Justice Minister <PERSON> Kobie </PERSON> <PERSON> Coetsee </PERSON> said two former security policemen whose allegations prompted the inquiry would be prosecuted. One awaits execution for a non-political murder and the other has fled the country. `` The government has full confidence that the tried and respected prosecution mechanisms of the state will be sufficient to bring the accused before the court, impartially and objectively,'' <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON> in response to demands that the investigation be conducted outside the law enforcement establishment. `` A judicial inquiry can take months, if not years, to reach its final conclusions,'' he said. `` In the meanwhile, a climate of suspicion and distrust could develop, something the country can ill afford at this stage in its history.'' <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s national police have been criticized for failing to solve dozens of killings of anti-government activists since 1978. Anti-apartheid leaders say many people believe security personnel help plan, participate in, or cover up such actions. Three former security policemen have said in recent newspaper interviews or sworn affidavits that they participated in death squad operations on orders of superiors, many of whom still occupy high positions in the police. The former policemen, two black and one white, said they were involved in bombings, ars