TION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> blacks more than 2-to-1, the mood seemed mostly concerned but not hostile. `` Yes, there will be people in the Hispanic community that will think it's unfair, but that has to be settled,'' said <PERSON> Tere </PERSON> <PERSON> Gavalda </PERSON> of the Spanish-American League Against Discrimination. `` It's unfortunate the case turned out to be a black against Hispanic issue We have to put that to rest.'' Mayor <PERSON> Xavier </PERSON> <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> said he received nearly a dozen telephone calls from people angered by the verdict, but there was no indication of violence. <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON>, who last summer was denounced by some fellow Cuban-Americans for supporting a black woman over a Cuban for a city commission seat, said there was no way of knowing if the verdict would raise tensions between blacks and Hispanics. `` I do n't think the Hispanic community is going to respond in any monolithic way,'' <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON>, who took office in 1985 with a promise to improve <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>'s inner-city neighborhoods, hoped the verdict might ease some of the alienation among blacks there who feel the justice system is against them. `` There has been a succession of cases that led to outcomes that have not been successful to the black community,'' <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> said. `` This was at least a departure from a trend.'' Community leaders who had been ready to go into the streets to talk against violence said they would try to ease any ethnic reactions by Hispanics. `` We definitely have not reached Utopia,'' said <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Sims </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Community Relations Board. `` We're not going to drop everything. We were focusing on a not guilty verdict -LRB- and black reaction -RRB- and now the emphasis shifts on the Hispanic group.'' At Spanish-language radio station <ORGANIZATION> WQBA </ORGANIZATION>, caller were shocked and angry, said <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Checa </PERSON>, a technical director. `` Mostly, they feel the judgment was done for the black community,'' <PERSON> Checa </PERSON> said. Some police advocates predicted the verdict would harm efforts to recruit for <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>'s police force. `` I hope this wo n't discourage people from being police officers, but that's my concern. Being a cop in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> is tough enough,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Nevel </PERSON>, attorney for a police group that supports stronger penalties for criminals and also president of <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beach </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fraternal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Order </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>.
