<DATELINE>MORONI, Comoro Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Presidential Guard used tear gas and clubs to disperse about 1,000 students Thursday during the largest protest yet against European mercenaries who seized control of this island nation. Witnesses said several of the high-school students were beaten. The violence came as <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> cut off its $ 18 million in annual aid to the Comoros, off the east coast of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Diplomatic sources said the assistance would not be resumed until the head of the new ruling group, French mercenary <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Denard </PERSON>, leaves the island. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, another large donor to this impoverished nation with a population of about 430,000, took the same action Monday. It also cut off support for the Presidential Guard. President <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdallah </PERSON> <PERSON> Abderrahmane </PERSON> died Nov. 26 in an attack blamed by diplomatic sources on <PERSON> Denard </PERSON>, commander of the 500-member Presidential Guard. That force disarmed the regular army and now controls the four-island archipelago between <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> and the island of <LOCATION> Madagascar </LOCATION>. The students shouted `` The mercenaries must go!'' and `` <PERSON> Denard </PERSON> is an assassin!'' as they marched from the <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> to the beachfront Thursday morning. They were confronted there by members of the guard, which is led by about 30 French and Belgian mercenaries. The guardsmen, supported by jeeps equipped with heavy machine guns, drove through the capital in the biggest show of force since <PERSON> Abdallah </PERSON> was killed. <PERSON> Denard </PERSON> has denied involvement in the assassination, but sources said Thursday the two men had quarreled recently over several issues, including funding of the Presidential Guard. Many students dashed into the water when the guardsmen arrived, and others fled through side streets. Most later regrouped at the Ministry of the Interior in the city center, where dozens of guardsmen launched tear-gas grenades and charged with clubs. Youths forced a suspected spy for the Presidential Guard from his civilian car, then overturned the vehicle and burned it on one of the main streets of <LOCATION> Moroni </LOCATION>, the capital. Witnesses said several students were clubbed or otherwise beaten, but there was no official injury toll. Guardsmen patrolled working-class areas of the city throughout the day, dispersing smaller gatherings with tear gas and clubs, the witnesses said. Throughout the day, hundreds of young men jeered and shouted at Guard vehicles as they sped through the capital and outlying villages. `` The people have always opposed the mercenaries, but they were silent until the president was killed,'' said <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Moroni </LOCATION> resident. `` Now the people are angry and say the mercenaries must leave.'' Several photographers and reporters had their film and notebooks seized as they covered the morning demonstration. Ten journalists were later ordered to leave the islands by Thursday evening, and five other journalists were told to remain in their hotel. The French <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said the suspended aid includes direct assistance, as well as 150 technical and 13 military advisers. The islands gained independence from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in 1975. <PERSON> Denard </PERSON>, 60, ousted and later returned <PERSON> Abdallah </PERSON> to the presidency in coups during the 1970s. Although <PERSON> Denard </PERSON> held no official title, he maintained strong influence in security and political matters.
