<HEAD>Havel Says He Would Become President if Crisis Required</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Vaclav </PERSON> <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>, who only a month ago was reviled by the official press, said Thursday he would accept the presidency if necessary to help resolve the country's crisis. Appearing at a crowded news conference in the <LOCATION> Laterna </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Magika </LOCATION> theater, the playwright seemed tired but elated by his speedy transfer from the dramatic to the political stage. Thousands of supporters of <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s Civic Forum opposition movement, which <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> heads, are now sporting Hungarian-made buttons declaring `` Havel for President.'' With characteristic humor, <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> told reporters, `` I do n't wear that badge.'' He said he had nothing to do with its manufacture because `` my connections do not extend as far as <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>.'' A shy man, he has repeatedly declined offers to seek political office. But, when asked Thursday if he would accept the presidency if offered, he said he would do so under certain circumstances. `` I have repeatedly said that my occupation is a writer and that I have no political ambitions. I do n't feel myself to be a professional politician but have always put the public interest ahead of my own. `` And, if <PERSON> God </PERSON> help us, the situation should develop in such a way that the only service I could render my country would be to do this, then, of course, I would do it,'' <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> said. He stressed that there is no organized group promoting his candidacy. `` The more democratic and more normal the condition in our country, the less my role will be,'' the mustachioed writer said. <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> has avoided interviews the past two hectic weeks during a mass pro-democracy movement that forced the Communists to relinquish their 41-year monopoly on power, ousted most hard-line leaders and paved the way for a coalition government that could restore democracy. With characteristic caution Thursday, he ducked a question about when he began to believe that the opposition could triumph. `` We have a saying in Czech, ` You should not praise the day before the evening,''' <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> said, smiling. As a founding member of Charter 77, eastern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s oldest human rights movement, <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> has spent most of the last 13 years under police surveillance and served 4 -LCB- years in jail for his outspoken criticism of what he calls `` totalitarian Communism.'' Asked what he had learned from those years, <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> echoed the creed of one of his best-known essays chronicling the moral deformations of Stalinism, `` Living In Truth.'' `` I have learned that when a person behaves in accordance with his conscience, and when he tries to speak the truth, behave as a citizen even when citizenship as such is degraded. It may not lead to anything _ but it might,'' he said quietly.
