<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The General Assembly voted overwhelmingly in favor of a resolution Thursday that calls on the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to stop financing <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Contra rebels. The assembly passed by a 91-2 margin the Nicaraguan-sponsored resolution against the U.S-backed Contras, who were to be disbanded this week under a regional peace plan. It asked <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to obey a 1986 judgment by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> ordering it to halt support for the Contras. Only the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> voted against the measure. The 41 abstentions included most of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> allies in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, where an estimated 11,000 Contra forces are headquartered in jungle camps along the Nicaraguan border, also abstained. In a separate action, the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> decided by consensus to approve spending up to $ 40.8 million over six months to send a 650-member border patrol force to <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. The peacekeeping force is intended to deter cross-border raids by the Contras or any other insurgents and to cut off weapons-smuggling. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> accuses <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> of shipping weapons to leftist rebels battling <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON>'s government, and the Contras have acknowledged they are selling weapons to the Salvadoran rebels. <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON> told the assembly that the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s ruling was one-sided, ignoring <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support for the Central American peace process. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had said it not believe the world court, based in the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> and serving as the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION>'s judicial arm, could rule on national security issues. The court's 15 judges ruled <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> had disobeyed international law by interfering in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s internal affairs with its support for the Contras. The court has no power to enforce its judgments, however. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military aid to the Contras ended two years ago, <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON> said, and only non-lethal aid is sent to the rebels. By contrast, he said, `` <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s military assistance to the <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> insurgents has again been revealed in the recent plane crash at <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Transito </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, which revealed weapons destined for the <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> guerrillas.'' Two dozen Soviet-made SAM-7 anti-aircraft missile launchers were found in the wreckage of that light plane, which crashed Nov. 25. Nicaraguan Ambassador <PERSON> Alejandro </PERSON> <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON> <PERSON> Caldera </PERSON> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> `` aggression'' against <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> continues today. He said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> non-lethal aid to the Contras is actually logistical help in the war. In addition, <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON> <PERSON> Caldera </PERSON> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> meddling in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s internal affairs continued when the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> appropriated $ 9 million for the opposition in national elections set for Feb. 25 Under an agreement signed by Central American presidents, the Contras were to be dismantled voluntarily by last Tuesday. However, neither the rebels nor the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> were part of that accord. President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> has proposed extending the deadline to the end of the month. The region's presidents are meeting again Sunday in <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> to take up the issue.
