 <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moe </PERSON>, honored last summer as the oldest survivor of the attack on <LOCATION> Pearl </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>, died Dec. 1. He was 99. <PERSON> Moe </PERSON> was an engineering officer on the <ORGANIZATION> USS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Curtis </ORGANIZATION>, a seaplane tender hit by a single Japanese bomb during the attack that led to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> involvement in World War II the next day. A career <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officer, he retired in the early 1960s and devoted his time to numerous Norwegian-American organizations. When <PERSON> Moe </PERSON> turned 99 on July 6, the <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> chapter of the <ORGANIZATION> Pearl </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harbor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Survivors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> presented him with a plaque for being the oldest survivor of the attack.
