<HEAD>Airline Chief Apologizes To Idaho Governor, Mayor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to CORRECT title of Lorenzo to chairman,
sted president, of Continental Airlines; CLARIFIES total number of passengers
killed; picks up 5th graf: `Mayor Dirk ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> has written to Gov. <PERSON> Cecil </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrus </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION>'s mayor apologizing for an advertisement run in <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> belittling the city. The Houston-based airlines also has changed its advertising policy to prevent a similar incident, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> officials said Tuesday. <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Andrus </PERSON>' press secretary, said an apology was the least <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> could do. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> also is chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>'s parent company. The governor took exception to a jibe in the ads that asked how often someone would need to go to <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Andrus </PERSON> called it a `` cheap shot'' in light of the 1987 <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> crash of a Boise-bound <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> flight that killed 28 people, 14 of them Idahoans. Mayor <PERSON> Dirk </PERSON> <PERSON> Kempthorne </PERSON> said he appreciated the apology but still wanted follow-up advertisements in <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> aimed at boosting <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION>'s stock as a destination for air travelers. The advertisement, since yanked from publication, pitched 2-for-1 tickets from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> and other destinations. The ad admitted there are a few places in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> does not serve, but asked, `` But be honest, how often do you really need to go to <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>?'' <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> pulled out of <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION> and seven other Western <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cities in September 1988, saying it would focus on more profitable routes. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> wrote in the letter to <PERSON> Andrus </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kempthorne </PERSON>, sent by fax machine late Monday, that `` my view of advertising does not include poking fun at any city. `` Furthermore, a copywriter could not have chosen a more unsuitable target for his weak pun. I was appalled to see the effect of these coinciding mistakes,'' <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> wrote. `` Both <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> share many unhappy memories brought on by the <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> accident. I want to continue to do everything possible to mend the wounds that resulted from the tragedy,'' he wrote. Continental has maintained that the ad prepared by a British advertising firm was conceived by people who had no knowledge of the <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> crash and was not reviewed at corporate headquarters until after publication. <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Kent </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> vice president of corporate communication, said a new policy has been adopted. `` All advertising done overseas has to be approved and cleared before publication here at the <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> headquarters,'' <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
