<SECOND>AM-Religion Today, Adv 08,0830</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday AMs, Dec. 8, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Catch 22' Trap Claimed in School Bible Club Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Some call it a `` Catch-22'' snare, zapped if they do, and zapped if they do n't. That's the predicament claimed for some students at <ORGANIZATION> Westside </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, who want an off-hours Bible club. The problem has surfaced at numerous public schools across the country. Federal courts have issued conflicting opinions about it, and although <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has passed a special law allowing for such clubs, the issue is now before the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. Several church groups, supporting student rights to form such groups, contend Westside put a double-nix on it, barring the club for lack of school sponsorship, although such sponsorship would make the club unconstitutional. Either way, it's out, according to the school board's position, amounting to a `` self-imposed Catch-22'' for the students, the church groups say in a brief supporting the students' appeal to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. Efforts at organizing such clubs, strictly by student initiative and without official school involvement, has had a rocky and litigious course in many communities throughout this decade. Trying to dispel the confusion, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> adopted the Equal Access Act in 1984, guaranteeing student religious groups the same rights to meet in off-class hours as other non-academic, extracurricular groups. The law was based on rights of free speech _ that schools with a `` limited open forum'' allowing students to organize clubs about politics, dancing, archery, bridge or whatever also must allow clubs that talk religion. But schools have remained skittish about any religious inklings on campus ever since the 1962-63 high court decisions banning sponsored prayer or Bible readings. `` Some educators have come to believe that all religious speech must be extirpated from the schools,'' the churches' brief says, but such a view fails to distinguish between officially sponsored speech and individual rights. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> sought to end discrimination against student religious speech but the brief says `` this case shows that at least some local school officials fundamentally reject each and every premise on which <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> acted.'' On the other hand, the American Jewish Committee, which opposes the act, has filed a brief contending that to allow a school religious club would `` open the door to organized religious activities in public schools.'' In a dispute at the <LOCATION> Wiliamport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, high school, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 affirmed the right of students to meet for Bible and prayer outside classtime, but the case was decided on a technical point not generally applicable. Early this year, a federal appeals court ruled against a student religious group at a <LOCATION> Renton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, high school, giving the school discretion to allow clubs considered even remotely related to education, but not if religious. In the dispute at Westside high school, a federal district court upheld the school board's refusal to allow a religious club while permitting about 30 other other clubs, such as for chess and scuba diving. But a federal appeals court overturned that decision, rejecting the school's position that the various clubs were curriculum-related. That claim, the court said, would allow a school administration simply to choose whatever clubs it wished for vague reasons, but then to `` discriminate against particular student groups'' because of religious speech. `` It would be tragic if the court allows a school board to eviscerate'' the Equal Acess Act `` by declaring all clubs except relgious ones to be ` curriculum-related','' says <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, general counsel for the <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Public Affairs. Other groups joining in the brief were the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scoiety </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evangelicals </ORGANIZATION>, the Presbyterian Church -LRB- USA -RRB- and the Church of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> of Latter-day <ORGANIZATION> Saints </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Catholic Bishops have filed their own brief, affirming rights of students to form voluntary Bible clubs. The brief says the action of the school officials, instead of upholding the Constitution, have created a constitutional problem `` by inhibiting religious activity and conveying a message of disapproval of religious activity to both the students involved and the community at large.'' Oral arguments before the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> are expected to be heard this month or early next year, with a decision by next summer. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Bridget </PERSON> <PERSON> Megens </PERSON>, who with friends initiated attempts for a Bible club at <ORGANIZATION> Westside </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in 1984 and is now married and the mother of a young daughter, says: `` I was afraid there might not be anybody to carry the torch.'' However, she says about 15 students still are pushing the effort. `` There are even some kids who are not Christians who are interested,'' she told the monthly Church and State. She says she hopes the dispute will be resolved so her daughter can belong to a Bible study group at her high school when she grows up.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Friday AMs, Dec. 8</NOTE>
