<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 10, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sketches of Chilean Presidential Candidates</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Chile Votes, b0517</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are brief sketches of the candidates in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s presidential election:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> PATRICIO </PERSON> <PERSON> AYLWIN </PERSON> _ An ex-senador and former president of the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the country's largest, <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> was nominated by an opposition alliance of 17 leftist and centrist political groups. Virtually every opinion poll gives him a commanding lead over his two opponents. At 71, he is the oldest candidate and was already a prominent politician when Gen. <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> seized power in a 1973 coup. Considered somewhat right-of-center, <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> initially supported the military takeover, but became disillusioned with <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s strong-arm tactics and reluctance to hand power back to civilians He gradually joined the ranks of the government's outspoken critics. He is known as an able negotiator with a low-key, conciliatory style, and he was the official spokesman for the opposition alliance when it successfully campaigned for the `` no'' vote in a referendum in October 1988, on a proposal that <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> remain president until 1997. That defeat forced <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> to call elections to pick a successor. In the campaign <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> has pledged to re-establish full respect for human rights and civil liberties and to increase spending on social programs. He has said he plans no major changes in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s free-market economic program
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> HERNAN </PERSON> <PERSON> BUCHI </PERSON> _ <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s finance minister from 1985 until last May, <PERSON> Buchi </PERSON> is considered the principal architect of a free-market economy that has produced five years of steady growth and low inflation. <PERSON> Buchi </PERSON>, 40, is an all-around athlete who runs several miles daily, climbs mountains and jumps horses. With a master's degree from <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s business school, he joined the <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> adminstration in 1975 as an Economy Ministry aide and rapidly ascended the bureaucratic ladder. He is considered highly intelligent but slightly eccentric. His trademark is a roughly trimmed page-boy haircut that once prompted <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> to dub him `` my Prince Valiant.'' One of the slogans of his campaign has been `` Buchi is different.'' Despite an international reputation as an able technocrat, he entered the race as a political novice. Indeed, he withdrew for several weeks in May and June, declaring he was too shy to be a candidate. He returned, he said, because of a sense of patriotic duty. Backed by conservative businessmen and rightist political groups, he has campaigned as the `` can-do'' candidate. He has promised a million new jobs during the next four years and said he will spend more on health and education.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> FRANCISCO </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> ERAZZURIZ </ORGANIZATION> _ From a prominent Chilean family that has produced several presidents, <PERSON> Errazuriz </PERSON> has dedicated most of his adult life to amassing wealth. The 47-year-old entrepreneur has built a commercial empire that consists of some 30 businesses including mining and fishing interests, automobile concessions, a fruit exporting company and a supermarket chain. All told, he employs about 8,000 workers. Characterized by his opponents as a populist, he has promised free health care and education to all Chileans. He is backed by a few small political groups. He describes himself as a `` centrist-centrist'' and says his candidacy offers Chileans an alternative to the traditional choice between leftist and rightist candidates. His nickname is `` Fra-Fra.'' One of his principal campaign slogans is `` No more bla-bla. Vote for Fra-Fra.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 10</NOTE>
