<SECOND>BC-The '80s-Disasters, Adv 16,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Dec. 16-17 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Decade of Catastrophe, Natural and Man-Made</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The Earth shook, erupted, collapsed, caught fire and spawned vicious storms with regularity through the 1980s, killing tens of thousands of people around the world. But the decade's cataclysms also included new forms of man-made tragedy. Here is a review of some of the decade's worst disasters:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>NATURAL DISASTERS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 MAY 18, 1980 _ <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Helens </LOCATION> volcano in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state erupts with power equivalent to 500 <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> bombs. This blast and two that followed within the next month killed 57 people and caused over $ 3 billion in damage. OCT. 11, 1980 _ Earthquake in <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> kills 6,000 and leaves 400,000 homeless. NOV. 23, 1980 _ More than 3,000 killed and 300,000 left homeless when earthquake, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s deadliest in 65 years, devastates southern <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. MAY 24-25, 1985 _ Cyclone out of <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bengal </LOCATION> comes ashore in <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>; some 11,000 killed. SEPT. 19, 1985 _ Earthquake strikes <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>; 7,000 die. NOV. 13-14, 1985 _ <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s erupting <PERSON> Nevado </PERSON> <PERSON> del </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruiz </PERSON> volcano melts snowcaps, causing a massive mudflow that buries town of <LOCATION> Armero </LOCATION>, killing 25,000 people. AUG. 21, 1986 _ Cloud of toxic gas from volcanic <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nios </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Cameroon </LOCATION> envelops several villages, killing 1,746 people and injuring 874. MAY 7, 1987 _ Approximate start of series of <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> forest fires that kill 191 people. SEPT. 12-16, 1988 _ Hurricane <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON>, Category 5 storm with winds up to 160 mph, strikes <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cayman </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, killing some 300 people. OCT. 19-25, 1988 _ Hurricane Joan-Miriam kills 184 in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. DEC. 7, 1988 _ Earthquake registering 6.9 on <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale kills 25,000 in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. SEPT. 17-21, 1989 _ Hurricane Hugo sweeps through <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> and into <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, with 135 mph winds, killing 62. OCT. 17, 1989 _ Earthquake measuring 7.1 on <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale rattles <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> area, killing 67 and causing estimated $ 7 billion in property damage.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>TRANSPORTATION DISASTERS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 AUG. 12, 1985 _ In decade's worst air disaster, <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> 747 crashes into a mountain near <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, killing 520. Four passengers survive crash. DEC. 12, 1985 _ Arrow Air charter DC-8 crashes shortly after takeoff from <LOCATION> Gander </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION>; all 256 people aboard die, including 248 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> servicemen. AUG. 16, 1987 _ In decade's worst <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> domestic plane crash, <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> MD-80 crashes on takeoff at <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Metropolitan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, killing 156. One passenger, a 4-year-old girl, survives. DEC. 20, 1987 _ <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> passenger ferry <PERSON> Dona </PERSON> <PERSON> Paz </PERSON> collides with tanker and sinks; more than 3,000 holiday travelers killed. JUNE 4, 1989 _ Gas explosion in <LOCATION> Ural </LOCATION> mountains of <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> engulfs two passing trains, killing 645.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>INDUSTRIAL ACCIDENTS and FIRES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 MARCH 27, 1980 _ Offshore platform housing oil workers capsizes in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> off <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, killing 123 men. NOV. 21, 1980 _ Fire at <ORGANIZATION> MGM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> kills 87 people. FEB. 15, 1982 _ World's largest floating oil drilling rig, <ORGANIZATION> Ocean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ranger </ORGANIZATION>, sinks in storm off coast of <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION>, killing 84. DEC. 3, 1984 _ Leak of deadly methyl isocyanate gas at <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> plant in <LOCATION> Bhopal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, kills 3,598 people, injures 20,000. APRIL 26, 1986 _ Explosion and radiation leak from <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear power station kills at least 31, hurts some 300. Later unconfirmed report says 250 died. SEPT. 16, 1986 _ South African gold mine fire kills 177. DEC. 31, 1986 _ Fire at <ORGANIZATION> Dupont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plaza </ORGANIZATION> hotel in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, kills 97. Three hotel employees later plead guilty to arson charges. JULY 6, 1988 _ <ORGANIZATION> Piper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION> oil platform explodes in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, killing 167.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions Dec. 16-17 and Thereafter</NOTE>
