<HEAD>$adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Dec. 16-17 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Mounting Toll: Victims of a Plague</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 It was the great untold story of the 1980s. Or was it in the newspaper every day? Suddenly, an unusual number of people in their prime were dying _ `` after a long illness,'' their obituaries often said. Though frequently written with respect for personal or family wishes, the vague death notices deflected early public attention from a toll that would mount to almost 70,000 Americans, victims of a virus, discovered only in 1983, that infected an estimated 6 million to 8 million people worldwide by the end of the'80s. Halfway through the decade, the death of movie star Rock Hudson personalized for many Americans what had been a faceless plague, seemingly limited to `` risk groups'' of homosexual men, hemophiliacs and intravenous drug users. By then, the infections and cancers that could drastically shorten the lives of those infected with the virus had a name, acquired immune deficiency syndrome _ AIDS. Quickly, other well-known names in the arts and public life were drawn into the patchwork of torn lives symbolized by an immense quilt spread in front of the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Monument. Just as the quilt has grown too large to be shipped around the country for display, the roster of the dead can only be represented symbolically by this short list:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1985</NOTE>
<NOTE>ROCK HUDSON@ _ Actor who epitomized the clean-cut American male</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 in movies for more than 20 years. His films included `` Written on the Wind,'' `` Magnificent Obsession'' and `` Giant.'' Oct. 2, age 59.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1986</NOTE>
<NOTE>PERRY ELLIS@ _ Sportswear designer and fashion maverick. May</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 30, age 46. Cause of death was said to be viral encephalitis, but credible reports linked his death to AIDS.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ROY COHN@ _ Lawyer who was friend and counselor to both</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 cardinals and mobsters; controversial Communist-hunter who served as chief counsel for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>. Aug. 2, age 59.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WAY BANDY@ _ Top makeup artist and author of best-selling</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 beauty book. Aug. 13, age 45.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>JERRY SMITH@ _ All-Pro tight end for the Washington Redskins in</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 1965-1977. Was first professional athlete known to have died of AIDS. Oct. 15, age 43.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>TERRY DOLAN@ _ Conservative activist and founder of the</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Political </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> NCPAC </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, whose fundraising techniques changed modern political campaigning. Dec. 28, age 36.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1987</NOTE>
<NOTE>LIBERACE@ _ Flamboyant pianist who combined glitter with music</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 and became one of the nation's most enduring entertainers. Feb. 4, age 67.
</TEXT>
