<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Cholesterol Adv11   12-07 1295</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Cholesterol, Adv 11,1329</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Dec. 11, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Scientific Camps Still Sorting Out Cholesterol</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As Americans wend their way through the season of holiday goodies and then decide what diet to choose for the New Year, they face a smorgasbord of scientific updates and debate over cholesterol. A 2-year-old government campaign to get people interested in knowing how much of the fatty substance is in their arteries has made cholesterol a popular topic from cocktail parties to medical-screening booths in shopping malls. Researchers are releasing new studies detailing how excess cholesterol _ an essential building block of cell membranes, sex hormones and Vitamin D _ in the blood clogs vessels and causes heart attacks. Food manufacturers are devising new products to capitalize on the findings, splashing `` cholesterol-free'' banners across items ranging from cupcakes to peanut butter, which never contained cholesterol anyway. News media have kept the public's curiosity piqued with the views of a small but vocal group of critics, including scientists. They say the public is being frightened needlessly, many people wo n't benefit from the low-cholesterol diets, and money is wasted to try to get <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to change the way it eats. How bad is cholesterol? How hard should people work to avoid it? And how much will that help increase their chances of living longer? Researchers have spent hundreds of millions of federal dollars trying to answer those questions; many top scientists are convinced of the results. `` The evidence linking elevated blood cholesterol to coronary heart disease is overwhelming,'' a group of them said recently in a statement by the American <ORGANIZATION> Heart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and the National Heart, Lung and <ORGANIZATION> Blood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. Population studies, clinical trials, genetic tests and animal experiments show that high levels of blood cholesterol clog arteries and increase the risk of heart disease, they said, adding clinical trials show lowering cholesterol levels by diet or drugs decreases subsequent occurrence of heart disease. `` The direct evidence ... is strongest in middle-aged men with high initial cholesterol levels,'' but also strongly suggests cutting cholesterol is likely `` to decrease coronary heart disease incidence in younger and older men, in women, and in persons with more moderate cholesterol levels,'' they said. Two of the largest studies to date suggest that a 1 percent reduction in blood cholesterol translates into a 2 percent reduction in the risk of developing coronary heart disease, they added. Those studies _ the <ORGANIZATION> Coronary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Primary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prevention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trial </ORGANIZATION>, involving more than 3,800 middle-aged men, and the Framingham Heart Study of over 5,000 women and men _ have been supported by others suggesting greater benefit, they said. However, critics of the anti-cholesterol campaign contend it has misled people by excluding mention of other major contributors to heart disease, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s No. 1 killer, which claims more than 500,000 lives a year. One critic, Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Olson </PERSON>, professor of medicine and pharmacological science at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Stony </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brook </LOCATION>, says only about 20 percent of a person's heart-disease risk is attributable to blood cholesterol. An estimated 40 percent is hereditary and the rest is due to other causes, chiefly smoking and high blood pressure, he said. `` We think there's too much hype in the marketplace and even in these educational agencies. Everybody's sort of afraid of their food and afraid of their cholesterol, often without medical surveillance.'' Dr. <PERSON> Fredrick </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stare </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> nutrition professor emeritus and co-author of `` Balanced Nutrition: Beyond the Cholesterol Scare,'' agrees. `` We do n't think the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cholesterol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> gives enough attention to other risk factors that are more important _ smoking, high blood pressure, obesity, diabetes, lack of a reasonable amount of activity and stress.'' Dr. <PERSON> Eliot </PERSON> <PERSON> Corday </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, past president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cardiology </ORGANIZATION>, said he objects to cholesterol-lowering efforts for people over 65. `` Over 65, there's no proof there's any benefit,'' said <PERSON> Corday </PERSON>, formerly a member of the advisory council to the National Heart, Lung and <ORGANIZATION> Blood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, where he felt `` very, very outnumbered'' by ardent cholesterol opponents. Elderly patients `` try very hard not to touch a bit of cholesterol,'' <PERSON> Corday </PERSON> said, even though `` it's a damn fool thing to stop eating eggs and meat when they need the nutrition. They get anemic.'' The <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Physicians </ORGANIZATION> recommended in February that checking family histories for heart attacks is more important than cholesterol testing, said <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON>, professor of medicine at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sinai </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>. `` I agree with them. If a lot of people in the family did n't have heart attacks, you're not going to have one. Cholesterol testing becomes appropriate if the family history suggests a genetic tendency to heart attack, he said. Cholesterol-modifying efforts should begin only if blood levels are high for so-called `` bad cholesterol'' _ LDL, or low-density lipoprotein _ and low for so-called `` good cholesterol'' _ HDL, or high-density lipoprotein. <PERSON> Olson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Corday </PERSON> and <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> were on a panel assembled in September by the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, a consumer education group partly funded by the food industry, to offset what they call the cholesterol `` scare.'' Part of their message was that only 15 percent of the population have blood-cholesterol levels putting them clearly at greater risk for heart attacks. That level is generally agreed to be 240 milligrams per deciliter of blood, and people testing that high `` should be seeing a physician ... They should not be self-medicating themselves'' with diet changes, said <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Whelan </PERSON>, the council's president. Besides, lowering cholesterol dietarily is difficult at best and impossible for many; not everyone responds the same way. Confusion also prevails about what to modify in the diet, with undue emphasis placed on cholesterol, <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> said. `` We make three times as much cholesterol from dietary fat as from dietary cholesterol. Too much -LRB- dietary -RRB- cholesterol is not the culprit. Too much saturated fat is the culprit.'' Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> LaRosa </PERSON>, chairman of the task force on cholesterol issues for the American <ORGANIZATION> Heart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, says critics `` are not really saying anything different'' from the government scientists. Their guidelines are unchanged since being introduced two years ago as part of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cholesterol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION>, which recommends that all adults learn their blood-cholesterol level and aim for a level below 200 milligrams per deciliter of blood. Those with levels of 200-239 are considered borderline high, not requiring treatment unless they have two other traits that increase their risk for heart disease, including hereditary tendency and being male. People who head for shopping malls or other public places to get their cholesterol checked should be wary, though. The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> said last month that such screenings can be inaccurate, pose health risks and frequently fail to provide counseling or physician referral. Those with confirmed levels of 240 or above are at high risk and should get HDL and LDL testing. If warranted, treatment should begin with diet and exercise, and should proceed to drugs only if that approach fails. The scientific basis for the guidelines `` is probably more solid than for any public health venture that I know of,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, a professor of medicine at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> was chairman of the federal 1984 <ORGANIZATION> Concensus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> panel that gave rise to the assault on cholesterol. `` It has been tremendously effective in bringing in people who have been previously unwilling to listen to lifestyle modifications,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickey </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> board member. Seventeen European nations in 1987 reached the same conclusions as the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> panel, and the Canadians did so later, <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> said. `` This is not sort of an off-the-wall conclusion by Americans who are gung-ho against cholesterol.''
</TEXT>
