<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--KillerBees Adv11   12-07 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Killer Bees, Adv 11,0667</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Dec. 11, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Federal Lab Develops Devices to Track Bees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAK RIDGE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Behind the security gates at <ORGANIZATION> Oak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ridge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION>, researchers are quietly preparing for an invasion. They've come up with one device to tell friend from foe and another to track the enemy. The invaders began their advance about 40 years ago and now are massing in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> for a final assault expected some time next year. No need to hustle down to the gun shop _ these invaders are aggressive Africanized bees, sometimes known as `` killer bees'' because they have killed animals and people. They've also disrupted honeybee colonies. Researchers at the federal laboratory here have developed a hand-held sensor that can distinguish between the tamer domestic honeybees and their more aggressive cousins, and a prototype of a device to track the Africanized bees using a solar-powered, infared-pulsating, microchip bee backpack. Neither device falls directly into the work done by the nuclear engineers and electronics specialists at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> lab </ORGANIZATION>. But they were intrigued by parallels with their work in connection with radiation monitoring. The $ 339 noise sensor, dubbed a `` Buzz <PERSON> Buster </PERSON>,'' is ready for market, said engineer <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerr </PERSON>, who developed it largely in his spare time. `` I've been to <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> twice and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> once with this thing and it works like a top.'' <PERSON> Kerr </PERSON>, an amateur beekeeper, got started a few years ago when told by a federal agricultural official that for some unexplained reason the Africanized bees that were released from a Brazilian lab make a louder sound in flight. The resulting <PERSON> Buzz </PERSON> <PERSON> Buster </PERSON> allows monitoring of a bee colony from a distance to determine whether there are any Africanized bees buzzing inside. While working on the Buzz <PERSON> Buster </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ker </PERSON> called in <PERSON> Chip </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> bee expert, who said what researchers needed was a way to track bees, particularly during mating. That sparked the idea for the microchip backpack. After a year of research and $ 100,000 in seed money from the lab, <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Alley </PERSON>'s team has developed a transmitter about one-fourth the size of a postage stamp that sends an infrared beam more than a 1 kilometer. An 8-inch telescope with a special sensor detects the beam, which ca n't be seen by the naked eye. Alley allows that the transmitter, at about 65 milligrams, is still 15 milligrams too heavy for a bee to carry, and work on a computerized tracking system has n't even begun. But `` I think we have proven the concept,'' he said. `` There are certainly some refinements that need to be made. But I think the concept is feasible. `` Today, I could n't give you a field demonstration of putting one on a bee. But several major hurdles have been crossed.'' But he said the hardest work has already been done, and the main job now is to get more funding to carry on. `` We've gotten interest from a broad spectrum of agencies, none of whom are interested in honeybees,'' <PERSON> Kerr </PERSON> lamented. `` There's a lot of things that people would like to be able to track with a very inconspicuous transmitter attached to it.'' <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> thinks the transmitters might be used for equipment inventories aboard spacecraft, and there have been inquiries from people who would like to use the microchip to track animals, birds and insects, <PERSON> Alley </PERSON> said. There also has been interest from the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and `` how would you characterize it? _ the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. Even if the transmitter is n't ready by the time the Africanized bees reach the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said, it will be developed eventually because of the number of possible applications. `` This is a technology that has to come along. If it does n't come along right now, it's got to come along in the future.''
</TEXT>
