<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Briefs Adv11   12-07 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Briefs, Adv 11,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Dec. 11, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Scientist Develops Process To Clear Up Blurry Pictures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A computerized process to sharpen blurry photos by breaking them into millions of pieces and reassembling them could be a boon not only to family albums but also to police who use photographs to solve crimes. State police used <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murat </PERSON> <PERSON> Tekalp </PERSON>'s process when they investigated the death of a 7-year-old boy who was struck by a vehicle while he was camping out on a hill behind his home. The only evidence was a faint trace of tire marks on the boy's tent. Police clarified the photographs and concluded that the boy was struck by his father's pickup truck. The case has not gone to trial, but state police Investigator <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Booth </PERSON> said the process was essential. There are `` dozens of scenarios'' in which it could be used, such as photographs of license plates, documents and vehicles, said <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>'s special photographic unit in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` If you've got one big case it works on, it's golden,'' he said Tekalp, a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rochester </ORGANIZATION> electrical engineering professor, has only developed the process for still photographs, but he said moving pictures are his next subject. The computer process uses a high-resolution scanner to divide a negative into more than 2 million pixels. Calculations then are made about what caused the blur, the computer sorts the information and produces a clearer image, and then a new negative is made.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Scientists Show How Acid Rain Kills Red Spruces</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nitric and sulfuric acids in rain are killing mountain forests in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> by damaging the foliage _ crippling photosynthesis _ and by upsetting trees' nutritional balance, a researcher says. `` This finding is a surprise because sulfuric acid from acid rain was shown in previous studies to be harmless to crop plants,'' said <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON>, who based his findings on five years of field and greenhouse experiments. `` We have demonstrated that sulfuric acid at concentrations similar to those found in acidic mist and cloud-water seriously weakens the foliage, thus impairing the tree's photosynthetic process. At high concentrations, it kills the needles outright,'' said <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON>, a plant physiologist at <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Boyce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thompson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>. While sulfuric acid destroyed the foliage, nitric acid _ a form of nitrogen fertilizer _ upset the trees' balance of nutrients, he said. `` All plants need nutrients from the soil to grow. If we give them too much of one nutrient such as nitrogen fertilizer from the atmosphere and not enough of others the trees would develop chronic nutritional deficiencies, a factor detrimental to the health of the affected tree in the long run.'' Scientists have long suspected that acid precipitation has been the cause of mountain forest decline. Red spruce, which grow at high elevations across the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION>, are important for the pulp and paper industries. Sulfuric acid is formed in the atmosphere when sulfur oxides from the combustion of coal and oil undergo chemical reactions. Nitric acid is produced by internal combustion engines and from the combustion of oil and coal. <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON>'s findings will be published next year in the <ORGANIZATION> Canadian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>, the Water, Air and Soil Pollution Journal, and Physiologia Plantarum in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Dec. 11</NOTE>
