<HEAD>Fishery Officials Hooked on Old Coal Mines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT HARVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> pulled a whopper rainbow trout from the <LOCATION> Elkhorn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> last summer, his state-record catch spawned an idea. Officials marveled that the 11-pound, 3-ounce beauty thrived in springwater fed in part by an abandoned coal mine, and want to make it a fish hatchery. `` Trout are extremely fragile,'' said <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamrick </PERSON>, director of the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION>. `` They need so many factors in order for them to perpetuate themselves naturally.'' `` Most people, when they think of a coal mine, do n't think of a hatchery,'' said <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Phares </PERSON>, state assistant chief of cold water fisheries. Good sites for trout hatcheries are hard to find because many count on natural springs for water, <PERSON> Phares </PERSON> said. He and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Rahall </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> mining and natural resources subcommittee, insist water conditions at some old coal mines are just right to produce the big Water draining from coal mines is usually very acid because of the residue of high-sulfur coal. The mine that feeds the <LOCATION> Elkhorn </LOCATION> was always low in sulfur. <PERSON> Phares </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rahall </PERSON> refused to name the mine or give its location until it can be purchased. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will take up the project next year; it must approve $ 2.5 million to buy the mine and build the hatchery. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> would build the hatchery, with a series of concrete runways eight feet wide by 100 long to produce up to 200,000 fish a year, <PERSON> Phares </PERSON> said. The mine drainage would be recirculated, with some outside water added for volume. The prototype hatchery could spawn new life for many old mines, said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Zoia </PERSON>, staff director of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee. `` There's a lot of potential in the Appalachian area. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, vice president of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s southern chapter of Trout Unlimited, said there are high hopes for the hatchery `` Being a big trout fisherman, I think it's needed and it could very well turn out to be a big economic boost to <LOCATION> McDowell </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>.''
