<HEAD>Conference Board: Consumer Confidence Off in November</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Consumer confidence in the economy fell in November but remains relatively strong, the <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said. A survey of 5,000 households nationwide showed that buying plans for houses and cars are soft and that Americans are slightly less optimistic about their expectations for the economy in the coming months. The <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>'s consumer confidence index, released Wednesday, registered 114.4 for November, the lowest since November 1988. Twenty-six percent of survey participants said current business conditions are good, down from 28 percent in October and the lowest level in more than a year. But the percentage who thought the economy was bad also fell, to 15.3 percent from 16.9 percent. Respondents' outlook for economic conditions six months from now showed 17.4 percent thought conditions would improve, the lowest since April. In a separate report, the <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said the volume of help-wanted advertising in 51 major newspapers increased in October. The group said want-ad volume was rising in 69 percent of the newspapers, compared with 55 percent in September and 35 percent in August 1988, but down from 84 percent a year ago. The board's help-wanted advertising index rose to 150 from 148 in September, but was down sharply from 161 a year ago. `` There is no question that labor market activity is slowing down, as is the economy in general,'' <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> economist <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldstein </PERSON> said. `` The data on want-ad volume suggests that while the labor market is cooling off we are not on the verge of a recession.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> is a non-profit business organization that conducts economic research and provides