<HEAD>Fed Sold Dollars Heavily In August-October Period</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> spent nearly $ 6 billion from August through October to stem the dollar's rise and keep the currency in the trading range set with other major industrialized nations, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> reported. The quarterly foreign-exchange report released Wednesday by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> showed the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> sold $ 5.871 billion in exchange for West German marks and Japanese yen during the three months ended Oct. 31. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> said the government sold a total of $ 3.289 billion for Japanese yen and $ 2.582 billion for West German marks. The move, the government's second-largest unloading of dollars ever in a three-month period, comes on the heels of the record-setting sale of $ 11.92 billion in the quarter ended July 31. The dollar initially got a boost during the August-October quarter from a spate of favorable economic data. Because of the figures, which indicated the economy was not as sluggish as previously believed, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> was not inclined to push interest rates lower _ which kept returns relatively attractive on dollar-denominated securities. Gains in retail sales and employment and a better-than-expected trade report helped boost the dollar to its high during the period of 2.00 West German marks and 148.98 Japanese yen on Sept. 15. But a meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seven </ORGANIZATION> industrial nations in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> later that month produced a sharply worded statement criticizing the dollar's rise. The group _ which includes the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> _ favors a relatively weaker dollar, which is seen as helping reduce the huge <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit. The Group of Seven called the dollar's rise inconsistent with long-run fundamentals'' and said a further rise could `` adversely affect prospects for the world economy.'' The bulk of the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s intervention, which was coordinated with other leading central banks, occurred in the weeks leading up to the G-7 meeting and in several weeks following the gathering. `` Activities after the -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> G-7 </ORGANIZATION> meeting -RRB- were forceful,'' said <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Y </PERSON>. Cross, a <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> executive vice president who presented the report to reporters. `` We did act quite forcefully to reinforce the policy statement'' of the group. `` Since that time the dollar has trended downward,'' <PERSON> Cross </PERSON> said. By early October the dollar had plunged to 1.8650 West German marks and 138.60 Japanese yen. By mid-October, the upward pressure on the dollar had fully eased. Interest rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> _ traditionally far lower than <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> rates _ were higher, thereby shrinking the advantage the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had in terms of return to investors and reducing demand for dollars. Furthermore, more recent reports indicated sluggishness in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy that raised speculation the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> might ease credit to help prevent a recession. The spotlight shifted to foreign currencies, particularly the mark, which was bolstered by <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s bright economic prospects and the beginnings of a massive reform movement in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The dollar now is trading at about 1.76-1 .77 marks and 143-144 yen Currency traders are often keenly aware of the activities of central banks in the open markets, but the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s policy is to comment only well after the fact. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> does not provide any data on intervention by foreign central banks.
</TEXT>
