<FIRST>r f PM-US-ForeignRisk     12-07 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Foreign Risk,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>US to Protect Banks Against Long-Term Foreign Risks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal <ORGANIZATION> Export-Import </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> says it is willing to protect private banks against political violence and other risks in countries where they make loans to support purchases of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods. The bank did not specify any countries in its announcement Wednesday. The new guarantee could be given to lenders to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and other East European countries if, as many business people hope, laws are repealed that limit <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to those nations. In the past, the bank required the borrowing government to make a guarantee against financial loss from violence and foreign government actions when the money was lent over five years or more for a government purchase. Private projects required a guarantee from a private bank in the borrowing country. On loans made for less than five years, the <LOCATION> Export-Import </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> has sometimes covered political risks. On Tuesday the bank told its <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that there have been several requests that it take over the long-term political guarantee. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Macomber </PERSON>, the bank's president, said he expected there will be many more such requests in the future. <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Frey </PERSON>, a press officer at the bank, explained that this was because projects in some countries that had been delayed by international debt problems are now being brought up again. Foreign governments are unwilling to take on the risk of additional debt themselves, she suggested. She said requests for the new <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> guarantees have come from <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> and some Latin American countries. An Export-Import Bank guarantee often makes the difference in closing a deal. Other governments of industrial countries, especially <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, compete vigorously for international orders. Political risks include war, rebellion, confiscation, nationalization and the refusal of a foreign government to allow payments to leave its country. The bank said the new long-term guarantees will be available after the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government and the borrowing government have made an agreement that provides a way to settle disputes. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government's <ORGANIZATION> Overseas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Private </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> already offers similar insurance to Americans who make direct investments, not loans, in other countries. Some governments, especially in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, have been reluctant to make agreements on dispute settlement because they are unwilling to see trade disputes handled anywhere but in their own courts.
</TEXT>
