<HEAD>Eastern Objects to Methods Used in Investigation of Finances</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An extensive financial investigation of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> being made under the supervision of a federal bankruptcy court has raised objections from the airline. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Boies </PERSON>, an attorney for Eastern, told <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> Bankruptcy Judge <PERSON> Burton </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON> at a hearing Wednesday that the investigation's objectivity has been compromised because a large part of the work has been delegated to <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s unions Attorney <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON>, the examiner appointed by the bankruptcy court, has been conducting the inquiry into <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and their parent <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> since early September. <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> and more than 20 associates have been interviewing current and former officers of the companies, union leaders and others. <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> told <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON> he has received a list of complaints from <LOCATION> Boies </LOCATION> which contend, among other things, that the investigation has been `` too tough'' and `` too prosecutorial.'' The examiner said the magnitude of the task has led him to delegate some work, such as interviews, to union attorneys but that practice has n't hurt objectivity. Also at the hearing, <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON> postponed for two months consideration of a union request for a special trustee to be appointed to run Miami-based <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON> postponed from Dec. 15 to Feb. 15 a hearing on the trustee issue, in accordance with a request by <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON>. He also gave <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> until Feb. 15 to submit a report on his investigation. `` It's clear that the underlying examinations are proceeding with vigor, with a great deal of discomfort,'' <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON> said. The unions at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> had asked that a trustee be appointed to run the airline in place of current management soon after they went on strike on March 4. <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON> has postponed hearings on the question several times since then. Union attorneys objected Wednesday to <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON>'s request that the trustee issue be put off again, but they agreed that he needed more time to complete his inquiry. Attorneys for Eastern's major creditors supported both of <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON>'s requests. Eastern filed for bankruptcy protection on March 9 and has been rebuilding as a smaller airline by hiring workers to replace the striking Machinists, pilots and flight attendants. Contract talks are ongoing between <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and its pilots and flight attendants unions, which decided to end their 8 1 @ 2-month sympathy strikes shortly before Thanksgiving. The <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union is still on strike against the airline. The unions have accused <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> of stripping assets from Eastern. <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> is looking into past transactions between <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and sister carrier <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>. They include, for example, the transfer of the System One computer reservation system from <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> to <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> in April 1987 for about $ 100 million. The key question is whether <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> has been treating the three companies as one airline, <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> told the court. He and his staff have interviewed around 70 people and examined more than 200,000 documents, he said. In October, <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> had said he expected to complete the investigation by early December, and said his schedule had been delayed several times by lawyers for the parties involved.
