<HEAD>Sun Needles IBM About Cutbacks, Takes Partial Credit for IBM Woes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> McNealy </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Microsystems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, is needling rival <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> over its huge job cuts and said his computer company can take some of the credit for Big Blue's woes. <PERSON> McNealy </PERSON>, who introduced two important additions to Sun's SPARC desktop computer family Wednesday, predicted a bright future for his $ 1.8 billion company in the 1990s despite problems elsewhere in the industry. <PERSON> McNealy </PERSON>'s uncharacteristic jabs at <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> and Wall Street traders came in response to questions about the effect on the computer industry of <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s announcement Tuesday that it would cut 10,000 jobs in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and set aside $ 2.3 billion from its pretax profit to pay for the cuts. Asked in an interview Wednesday whether Mountain View-based Sun might make any cutbacks, <PERSON> McNealy </PERSON> quipped, `` Maybe we should and make the stock go up.'' <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s stock rose 37 -LCB- cents on Tuesday's announcement, but fell $ 1 Wednesday to $ 98.62 -LCB-. `` Look at what the analysts did,'' <PERSON> McNealy </PERSON> said. `` <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> made a statement yesterday that something is very wrong. They laid off a whole <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Microsystems </ORGANIZATION> worth of employees and they wrote off from profits more than we have in annual revenue. And their stock went up. `` That's a fundamental statement that, ` We do n't know what to do with our cash, so we might as well pay it out in dividends.' Which is what they're doing. `` Their stock went up because -LRB- analysts -RRB- said, ` <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> just washed all their dirty socks, they took huge reserves and they padded their balance sheet and income statement massively so that they're probably not going to have a bad quarter the next couple of quarters So I'll get in, ride it up ... then get out before they do the next one.'' <PERSON> McNealy </PERSON> noted that <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s moves were typical of many <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies. `` There are lots of -LRB- chief financial officers -RRB- in industry who say when you take a bath, take a big bath because that makes your stock price go up,'' he said. `` But is that any way to run a company? I do n't think so.'' That type of thinking, and the short-term opportunities it provides traders on Wall Street, he said, results from the rules set by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` I'm not blaming the traders. It's the rules,'' he said. The answer, he claims, would be to impose heavy income taxes on profits from stock held less than a year or two. <PERSON> McNealy </PERSON> said he has long predicted that the type of workstation computers Sun sells would cut into the sales of mainframe and minicomputer systems of companies like <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>. Workstations are powerful desktop computers that can be used for various applications, such as spreadsheets, word processing and database programming. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s mainframes and minicomputers are time-shared systems hooked to a large number of terminals, and all the applications are handled by the main processor. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> also makes personal computers. The three fastest-growing computer companies of the 1980s, <PERSON> McNealy </PERSON> said, were <ORGANIZATION> Compaq </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and Sun, all of which are desktop-oriented. That growth came at the expense of the companies that get most of their profit from the bigger, costlier computers, such as <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Amdahl </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Wang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Prime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION> Many industry analysts agree with <PERSON> McNealy </PERSON>'s views. `` It's fair to say that companies like <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Compaq </ORGANIZATION>, Sun, <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION> and others can take appropriate credit for <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s decade-long problems,'' said analyst <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> brokerage <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Stephens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` What's basically happened at <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> is their technology is obsolete,'' he said `` The model of computing on which they have built is no longer the preferred model.'' Sun's latest entries into its SPARC line are the powerful SPARCserver 490, which is priced at $ 113,900 with 32 megabytes of main memory, and an entry-level SPARCserver 1, priced at $ 18,900 with 8 megabytes of main memory. Founded in 1982, <PERSON> Sun </PERSON> has had only one quarter when it did n't show a profit Sun lost $ 20.3 million in the fiscal fourth quarter ended last June 30, blaming the slip on product transition and foulups in an internal computer management system. That cut its fiscal 1989 profit to $ 60.8 million on $ 1.8 billion in sales. The company recovered quickly, though, earning $ 5.2 million in the first quarter of its 1990 fiscal year. <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION> expects Sun will post $ 93 million in profits in fiscal 1990 on $ 2.5 billion in sales.
