<HEAD>Ex-Macmillan Chairman, 2 Execs Settle SEC Disclosure Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The former chairman of publishing giant <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and two current executives of the company have settled <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> charges alleging they filed misleading documents. The three _ <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON>'s chairman from 1980 to 1988; <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON>, <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON>'s chief operating officer; and <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chell </PERSON>, the publisher's general counsel _ were accused of filing misleading or incomplete documents concerning the purpose for buying 1.2 million <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> shares for a company employee stock option plan in 1987. In a civil complaint filed Wednesday at federal court in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> sought an injunction to prohibit the trio from violating federal securities rules. But simultaneously with the charges, the three _ without admitting or denying wrongdoing _ settled and consented to an injunction barring them from violating securities disclosure rules. A spokesman for <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> did not have an immediate comment on the settlement Wednesday evening. `` We believe it to be the first action the commission has brought in a filing by an <ORGANIZATION> ESOP </ORGANIZATION>, which are increasingly being used as a takeover defense,'' said <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Janick </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> attorney in the case. The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> complaint alleged that beginning in May 1987, <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chell </PERSON> began to develop a plan to recapitalize <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> in anticipation of a possible hostile takeover. <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> later headed a <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> management group that lost a takeover battle for <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> to <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> media lord <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON>. In 1988, a <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> court blocked a restructuring <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> proposed as a defense against an unwanted $ 1.9 billion bid from the <ORGANIZATION> Robert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. Bass later dropped his bid after competing offers were launched by the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Maxwell </LOCATION>. According to the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> complaint, as part of the alleged recapitalization proposal, <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chell </PERSON> caused <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION>'s employee stock ownership plan -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> ESOP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- to buy 1.2 million <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> shares, which was more than 5 percent of the then-outstanding stock. By law, persons or companies acquiring 5 percent or more of a company must disclose their stake and state their intentions in an <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> document known as a 13-D. But the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> charged that the 13-D filed by the trio did not disclose `` that a purpose of the acquisition was to further the recapitalization.'' <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>' lawyer, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, issued a written statement concerning the settlement, which said: `` Since the <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> ESOP </ORGANIZATION>'s purchase of <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> shares was extremely profitable to <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> employees, it satisfied the stated purpose of the transaction to allow ` employees to acquire stock ownership interest in the company.' `` Mr. <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> is pleased that the -LRB- SEC -RRB-'s action, alleging that a further statement of purpose was necessary, could be settled without spending the time and resources that would be required to litigate the commission's factual allegations and legal theories,'' the statement said.
