<FIRST>u f PM-SEC-ShortSellers     12-07 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SEC-Short Sellers,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Says It's Ready and Waiting to Catch Illegal Short Sellers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said it is ready to prosecute market manipulation by the practice of short selling _ but the evidence is n't always there. `` We're committed to identify short selling abuse wherever it may occur,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sturc </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>'s Enforcement Division told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel Wednesday. But he and another <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> official also told a subcommittee of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> `` short selling also provides the market with two vital benefits.'' <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ketchum </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>'s Division of Market Regulation, told the panel those benefits are market liquidity and price efficiency which help prevent volatility _ the steep price rises and drops that can panic investors and send the market plunging. But <PERSON> Sturc </PERSON>, an associate director of the enforcement division noted that he and <PERSON> Ketchum </PERSON> were `` not here to defend or attack short selling.'' In short-selling, an investor tries to take advantage of an anticipated drop in the price of a company's stock. The investor borrows stock from a broker and sells it, hoping to replace it with stock purchased at a lower price. The investor's profit would come from the difference between the price obtained for the borrowed stock and the lower price paid to replace it. Short selling is not illegal and stockholders are allowed to lend or borrow stock they are holding for customers, if the stock has been purchased on margin _ the buyer did not put up the full purchase price. But in testimony last week before the commerce, consumer and monetary affairs subcommittee, some witnesses complained some professional short-sellers often break the rules to get a stock to drop quickly and spread false rumors about a company, its products or its management. That testimony was about the over-the-counter market, which does not have the same rules governing short sales as do the stock exchanges. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION>, a private, self-regulating group oversees the over-the-counter market. <PERSON> Sturc </PERSON>, however, noted that the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> considers all complaints of short selling abuses, but often investigations `` do not lead to sustainable evidence of violations of the antifraud provisions of the federal securities laws.'' At the beginning of the hearing the subcommittee chairman, Rep. <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnard </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, D-Ga., said he was not sure `` that the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> is on the same wavelength as the subcommittee. But <PERSON> Sturc </PERSON> explained that often when companies complain they are the victims of short sellers spreading false rumors, there is no proof where the rumors originated or whether it has had an effect of the company's stock. `` We have a strong enforcement interest,'' said <PERSON> Sturc </PERSON>, adding `` I regret to say, Mr. Chairman, we have not received allegations of misconduct to quite the degree of specificity as has been presented to the subcommittee by several of the witnesses. We would be happy to receive them. My job is to try find violators and catch them and that's what I like to do.'' After the session, <PERSON> Barnard </PERSON> told reporters that the hearings were `` not a witchhunt as far as the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION> NASD </ORGANIZATION> were concerned. I thought there was good explanations.''
</TEXT>
