<HEAD>West German Mobile Phone License Awarded to International Consortium</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> today awarded a license to build and operate a private mobile telephone system that analysts estimate could be worth more than $ 5 billion to a four-nation consortium. Led by <ORGANIZATION> Mannesmann </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION>, the group also includes <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telesis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wireless </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lyonnaise </PERSON> <PERSON> des </PERSON> <PERSON> Eaux </PERSON> of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Deutsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Genossenschaftsbank </ORGANIZATION>, a major West German bank. The Post Ministry chose the consortium from a large field of contending groups, which included several of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s largest companies and international telecommunications concerns. The private network, called D-2, will compete with the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s own D-1 system. It will be the second digital cellular system in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The German government now operates an analog cellular network and plans to build its own digital system. <ORGANIZATION> Mannesmann </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kienzle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> GmbH </ORGANIZATION>, the electronics subsidiary of the West German engineering concern, will hold a majority stake in the consortium, called <ORGANIZATION> Mannesmann </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mobilfunk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> GmbH </ORGANIZATION>. Analysts have said that operating a mobile phone network in densely-populated <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> will be an extremely profitable business in the 1990s. The value of the license has been estimated at 2 billion to 10 billion marks, or the equivalent of about $ 1.1 billion to $ 5.6 billion. <ORGANIZATION> Mannesmann </ORGANIZATION> has said construction of the network will require initial investments of $ 2.2 billion. Rumors that the consortium won the bidding war spurred a rally in <ORGANIZATION> Mannesmann </ORGANIZATION> stock in recent days. Since last Thursday, <ORGANIZATION> Mannesmann </ORGANIZATION> stock has surged some 25 percent to close at 340.00 marks a share, or about $ 192, on Wednesday. The decision by Post Minister <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwarz-Schilling </PERSON> was based on a recommendation of a special advisory panel that ranked the <ORGANIZATION> Mannesmann </ORGANIZATION> consortium first among the bidders. <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Telesis </LOCATION>, which holds a 26 percent interest in the consortium, has not put a dollar value on its share of the license, but analysts estimate it could increase the per-share value of the company's stock by $ 3 or $ 4 as the financial market reacts to the announcement, company spokeswoman <PERSON> Amy </PERSON> <PERSON> Damianakes </PERSON> said. `` We view the cellular business as an ` <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>' opportunity,'' <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Ginn </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> PacTel </ORGANIZATION>'s president and chief executive officer, said in a news release today `` This license expands our reach into the international cellular market and provides significant potential for increasing shareowner value during the 1990s,'' <PERSON> Ginn </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Pacific </PERSON> <PERSON> Telesis </PERSON>, one of the `` Baby Bells'' created after the breakup of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, has a contract with the consortium to design, engineer and manage the new system's construction <ORGANIZATION> PacTel </ORGANIZATION>'s 26 percent interest covers about 16 million potential cellular subscribers, compared with its nearly 30 million potential subscribers in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ginn </PERSON> said. Other partners in the consortium are <ORGANIZATION> Mannesmann </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Deutsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Genossenschaftsbank </ORGANIZATION>, Cable and <ORGANIZATION> Wireless </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Lyonnaise </PERSON> <PERSON> des </PERSON> <PERSON> Eaux </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electrical </ORGANIZATION> and Automobile Trades.
