<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> says it wants to return to its roots, and some industry analysts are praising the move. The nation's third-largest automaker announced Wednesday that it has put its <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary on the block, sharply scaling back the company's diversification drive of earlier this decade. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> said it has hired <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to advise it on the sale of the aerospace and military technologies division. It did not disclose what price it might seek. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION> is comprised of <ORGANIZATION> Gulfstream </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a corporate jet maker that was acquired for $ 637 million in 1985; <ORGANIZATION> Electrospace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a maker of defense and electronics products and systems bought for $ 367 million in 1987; and <ORGANIZATION> Airborne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, formed in January 1989 by combining military aviation-related functions of <LOCATION> Gulfstream </LOCATION> and Electrospace. The vast majority of <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION>' 1988 revenue of $ 1.3 billion stems from <LOCATION> Gulfstream </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Stellman </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION>. Total <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> revenues in 1988 were $ 35.47 billion. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </OR