<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Phelps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> says it will take pre-tax charges of about $ 375 million in the fourth quarter to write down the value of certain assets that have been idle for several years. After deferred tax benefits, these charges will reduce net income in the quarter by about $ 250 million, or $ 7 per common share, the copper company said Wednesday, adding it still expected to report a profit for the period. `` The decision to take these charges at this time is unrelated to our outlook for copper and other market factors _ we remain bullish on the future,'' <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yearly </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer, said in a statement. Yearly noted that the Phoenix-based company `` has achieved record results for each of 1987, 1988 and the first three quarters of 1989, and there is a continuing strong market for copper and most of our other products.'' Included in the charges are about $ 145 million for reserve provisions for the <LOCATION> Morenci </LOCATION> smelter, about $ 50 million for the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cornelia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mine </ORGANIZATION>, Concentrator and Smelter in <LOCATION> Ajo </LOCATION>, and `` certain other facilities that have been rendered obsolete by environmental requirements or other economic considerations.'' The charges also reflect the reduction of about $ 115 million in assets stemming from the company's decision to indefinately defer any further pre-operating mine development work on the <LOCATION> Dos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pobres </LOCATION> underground copper deposit near <LOCATION> Safford </LOCATION>. `` These assets are assets that have been idle since 1984,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foster </PERSON>, a company vice president. `` Consequently, this is a non-cash charge to earnings that we feel we are not going to reactivate in the forseeable future.'' <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Moolick </PERSON>, who retired as president of <ORGANIZATION> Phelps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> in 1984, questioned the move. `` The Ajo mine, at the prices we've been experiencing, is a viable property,'' <PERSON> Moolick </PERSON> said. He closed the mine in 1984 when faced with plunging copper prices. However, <PERSON> Lew </PERSON> <PERSON> Alton </PERSON>, a managing general partner of the investment banking firm L.H. <PERSON> Alton </PERSON> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, praised the action. `` You figure they have new people at the helm, earnings are phenomenal ... and you get the opportunity to clean up the balance sheet. Why not do it when you have the chance?'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Phelps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION>'s net income for the quarter ended Sept. 30 was $ 115.4 million, or $ 3.26 a share, compared with net income of $ 93.3 million, or $ 2.53 a share, for the same quarter last year. In addition to its copper operations, <ORGANIZATION> Phelps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> produces carbon black, fabricates steel wheels and rims for trucks and manufactures magnet wire.
