<HEAD>Four-Nation Group To Build Mobile Phone Network Worth Billions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A four-nation consortium Thursday won the rights to build and run a private mobile telephone network in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, a license that some analysts say could amount to a $ 6 billion gold mine in the 1990s. The group led by <ORGANIZATION> Mannesmann </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION> also includes <PERSON> Pacific </PERSON> <PERSON> Telesis </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wireless </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lyonnaise </PERSON> <PERSON> des </PERSON> <PERSON> Eaux </PERSON> of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Deutsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Genossenschaftsbank </ORGANIZATION>, a major West German bank. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s current mobile phone network, operated by the government, is suffering from severe capacity restraints. A new network in the densely populated, economically strong country is considered certain to be a highly profitable enterprise in the next decade. But many analysts warn that implementation could face unforeseen delays or obstacles dueto changing regulation and increasing competition. `` We view the cellular business as an ` <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>' opportunity,'' <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Ginn </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telesis </ORGANIZATION>, said in a news release issued from the company's <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> `` This license expands our reach into the international cellular market and provides significant potential for increasing shareholder value in the 1990s,'' <PERSON> Ginn </PERSON> said. The Post Ministry chose the consortium from a large field of contenders that included several of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s largest companies and international telecommunications concerns. The private network, called D-2, will compete with the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s own D-1 system. Plans call for <ORGANIZATION> Mannesmann </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to start building separate networks in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in 1991 and complete them by 1994, Post Minister <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwarz-Schilling </PERSON> told reporters. The two systems will be integrated into a larger European network so the same cellular mobile phones can be used all over <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. That consideration is significant because of plans by the 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, known as the Common Market, to drop internal trade barriers by 1992 and create a unified market. Schwarz-Schilling said the new project will require investments of $ 1.1 billion to $ 2.3 billion. The private network should break even by 1995, he said. Analysts say D-2 could have 500,000 or more users by that time. <ORGANIZATION> Mannesmann </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kienzle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> GmbH </ORGANIZATION>, the electronics subsidiary of the West German engineering concern, will hold a 51 percent stake in the consortium, called <ORGANIZATION> Mannesmann </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mobilfunk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> GmbH </ORGANIZATION> and based in <LOCATION> Duesseldorf </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The final license agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Mannesmann </ORGANIZATION> will be signed in January, Schwarz-Schilling said. <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telesis </ORGANIZATION> will hold 26 percent of the consortium, DG-Bank 10 percent, Cable and Wireless 5 percent, and <PERSON> Lyonnaise </PERSON> <PERSON> des </PERSON> <PERSON> Eaux </PERSON> 2.5 percent. The remaining 5.5 percent will be held by various smaller shareholders. Other bidders for the license included German heavyweights like <ORGANIZATION> Bayerische </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motoren </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Werke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION>, the maker of <ORGANIZATION> BMW </ORGANIZATION> cars; <ORGANIZATION> Axel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Springer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Verlag </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION>, a major West German publisher; and several big industrial firms. Under a formula used by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> analysts to value mobile phone licenses, the order could be worth $ 6 billion. But others said that amount is too high because it does not consider necessary outlays and risks. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Verghese </PERSON>, electronics analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Deutsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, cautioned that a Europe-wide network could be delayed by disagreements within the European Community. He also said growing competition in coming years is likely to put pressure on profit margins. `` On paper it all looks wonderful, but the implementation could be delayed,'' <PERSON> Verghese </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Telesis </LOCATION> shares were up by 75 cents at $ 48.50 a share in late <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading. But <ORGANIZATION> Mannesmann </ORGANIZATION> shares dropped by nearly 2.8 percent in domestic trading after the announcement, on what traders called profit-taking following a recent runup in the stock due to speculation about the phone license. `` Everybody got carried away by the idea that <ORGANIZATION> Mannesmann </ORGANIZATION> got a license for printing money, but for the next three years we will see only costs,'' said <PERSON> Beate </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Seipen </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> stock analyst.
