<BYLINE>By PAIGE St. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRAVERSE CITY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of the customers on <PERSON> Denny </PERSON> <PERSON> Grinwald </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> charter boat this summer put the hard times facing the lake's sport fishing businesses into painfully clear perspective. `` He said, ` Captain, I understand there's bad news and good news on the lake. ... The bad news is I ca n't eat the fish I catch. The good news is I'm not going to be able to catch one.''' <PERSON> Grinwald </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Charter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, is n't laughing. What was, by <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> estimates, the cornerstone of a $ 1.6 billion Great Lakes fishery for <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> in 1985 has weakened dramatically. A bacterial disease seems to be decimating the lake's bread-and-butter sport fish, chinook salmon And this summer, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> issued a controversial warning that chemical contamination was making the fish a risky meal. Low catches and fish consumption warnings drove 140 <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> charter boats off the lake this year, leaving 876 operators where two years ago there were more than 1,000, <PERSON> Grinwald </PERSON> said Wednesday. More are expected to leave by spring. `` I know at least six boats from <PERSON> Ludington </PERSON> that will go to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> next year,'' <PERSON> Ludington </PERSON> charter captain <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Lacko </PERSON> said. `` That's bad. When you lose charter boats, you start losing motel rooms.'' <PERSON> Lacko </PERSON> estimates he lost half of his business in the past two years. `` The fishing is just not there,'' he said. <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>'s creel surveys show a 50 percent drop in the number of chinook salmon caught, said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> fish specialist in Madison. <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> surveys map a drop in the amount of time sport fishermen spent on the lake _ down from 3.5 million hours spent at nine ports in the mid-1980s to an estimated 1.8 million hours this year, said <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Rakoczy </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> biologist in <LOCATION> Charlevoix </LOCATION>. The chinook catch alone in the region from <LOCATION> Ludington </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Frankfort </LOCATION> _ along the middle western coast of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> along <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Lower </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> _ dropped from 242,000 fish in May and August of 1986 to 34,000 chinook the same period this year, <PERSON> Grinwald </PERSON> said. Chinook salmon, introduced into <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> more than 25 years ago to control an alien alewife population, are the dominant sport fish in the lake and make up more than half the catch, according to <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> record keepers. The salmon sport fishing industry supports not only charter operations but has helped revitalize many coastal towns. `` I've always felt the economic clout of the Great Lakes sport fishery is greatly undervalued,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Kitchell </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANI