<HEAD>Grand Met's Profit Up 23 Percent in Fiscal Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Grand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday that its net profit jumped 23 percent during its fiscal year, boosted by higher revenue from its food, beverage and retailing operations. The British conglomerate said its profit for the year ended Sept. 30 rose to 508 million pounds, or around $ 823 million, from 412 million pounds, or $ 667 million, the year before. Per-share earnings increased 18.6 percent to 55.6 pence, or 87 cents, from 46.9 pence, or 74 cents. Grand Met bought <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for $ 5.75 billion earlier this year. Revenue for the year soared 54.2 percent to 9.3 billion pounds, or $ 14.6 billion, from 6.03 billion pounds, or $ 9.5 billion. The gains included proceeds from the sale of the company's <ORGANIZATION> Intercontinental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotels </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clubs </ORGANIZATION> in December 1988 for more than 500 million pounds, or $ 810 million The greatest impact on the company's results came from <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>, which contributed 2.5 billion pounds, or $ 3.9 billion, to total revenue. Grand Met said intense activity to integrate <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> has included the sale of non-strategic businesses, such as its Bumble Bee and <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> foods operations. `` All parts of the business are performing strongly and management morale is high,'' the company said. Burger King, the fast-food chain which was owned by <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>, contributed 76 million pounds, or $ 119 million, to Grand Met's operating profit The parent company said it will take time for the benefits of a recent restructuring and quality improvement program to bear fruit, but `` the fundamentals of this business are very sound.'' Grand Met said sales from its food businesses, including those that were part of <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>, were strong in all divisions and are expected to climb 5 percent in the current quarter. But the slowdown in the British economy has been especially evident in the company's liquor sales over the last 12 to 15 months, said Grand Met Chairman <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheppard </PERSON>. The company likely will make further acquisitions and sales in the coming year but it is now prepared to consolidate its current businesses in food, beverages and retailing, <PERSON> Sheppard </PERSON> said. Grand Met did n't report quarterly or half-year results. It is not required to do so under British law.
