<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors adopted a plan Thursday to protect the company from hostile takeovers. The plan will allow shareholders to buy discounted stock in <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> if anyone buys 20 percent of the Stamford-based telecommunications company without <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION>'s permission. Under certain conditions, they could also buy stock in an acquiring company at a discount if <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> disapproved of the merger. `` The plan is not aimed at preventing a takeover of <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer. `` It is designed to encourage a buyer to negotiate with the board and to prevent abusive share-accumulation tactics. The rights will help the board ensure that all <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> shareholders realize the value of their investment in the company.'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said he was not aware of any efforts to take over the company. <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> said similar rights plans have been adopted by other telecommunications companies, including <LOCATION> Americtech </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Nynex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> had combined revenues and sales of $ 16.5 billion and net income of $ 1.2 billion last year from its telecommunications, lighting and precision materials businesses
