<HEAD>Diet Pepsi Jingle Becomes Battle Hymn in Cola Wars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Diet <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION>'s new `` The Right One'' advertising jingle has become a battle hymn for the cola wars, with the ad agency for rival Diet <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> disputing who owns the idea for the tune. The song was picked up for Diet <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION> after a similar version apparently was offered to rival Diet <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> as well as Budweiser beer. <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION>'s ad agency, <PERSON> Lintas </PERSON>: <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, complains that it should have been given the chance to buy the song before it was offered to anyone else, while <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION> is calling the protest a simple publicity stunt by its rival cola maker. <PERSON> Stone </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, executive vice president of Lintas: <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said the song used in the Diet <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION> television spot was written last year for <ORGANIZATION> Diet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION>, although it never was used publicly. <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> said he fired off a complaint letter to Sunday Productions, the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> music house that developed the song, after hearing the similar song in a Diet Pepsi ad during the Thanksgiving weekend. `` I'd like to believe they -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- did n't know it was ours and did n't buy it in a direct attempt to copy the industry leader,'' <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> said Thursday. But <PERSON> Hilary </PERSON> <PERSON> Lipsitz </PERSON>, president of Sunday Productions, said it was ludicrous for <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> or its ad agency to say they own the song. <PERSON> Lipsitz </PERSON> said he offered the song to other companies, including Budweiser brewer <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION>, after <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> rejected it for a possible ad campaign dubbed `` The Real One.'' `` There was no interest from <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION>. It was our song,'' <PERSON> Lipsitz </PERSON> said Thursday. `` It's pretty much as if they came to <LOCATION> Irving </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> and said, ` Write me a song' and did n't use it. Whose song would it be?'' <PERSON> Lipsitz </PERSON> said the tune was among several he presented to <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> said Diet <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> wanted a song as a back-up to its current ad campaign `` if and when the day came where we needed a substitute.'' `` Sunday Productions brought back some pieces of music developed from our concept,'' <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> said, adding that Sunday was paid a $ 10,000 `` demo fee.'' A commercial was prepared and then `` put on the shelf'' for possible use later, he said. <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> said <PERSON> Lintas </PERSON> should have been given the opportunity to buy the song outright before it was offered to anyone else. The agency is considering legal action, he said. Officials at the ad agency <ORGANIZATION> BBDO </ORGANIZATION> Worldwide who work on the Diet <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION> account, did not immediately return telephone calls Thursday. <PERSON> Becky </PERSON> <PERSON> Madeira </PERSON>, a spokeswoman at <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cola </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Purchase </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, headquarters called the complaints a publicity stunt by Atlanta-based rival <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's hard to find any other reason for all of this,'' she said. `` I understand the press had copies of the letters of complaint before the principals.'' Ms. <PERSON> Madeira </PERSON> said <PERSON> Diet </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepsi </PERSON> has been using the `` Right One'' slogan since August but had n't heard any complaints until the television commercial appeared last month. She also said <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION>'s application for a trademark for `` The Right One'' was made in July and drew no objection from <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> She said it is not unusual for companies to choose from several songs when considering an ad campaign. Ms. <PERSON> Madeira </PERSON> also said <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION> looks for music that reflects the character of its products, so it would be pointless to seek a song belonging to a competitor. `` It's hard to imagine that would make sense for either company,'' she said. `` Why would you advertise the personality of a competitor's product?''
