<HEAD>Dollar Closes Higher In Dull Dealings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede: LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar closed marginally higher against most foreign currencies Thursday, but trading was light and uneventful. Gold prices scored large gains in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dealings after finishing somewhat higher in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Technical factors were cited for driving prices higher. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, gold for current delivery ended at $ 410 a troy ounce, up $ 5.10 an ounce from late Wednesday. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted a troy ounce of gold bullion at $ 409.60 as of 4 p.m. EST, $ 5 higher than Wednesday's late bid Traders said the dollar traded within a very narrow range throughout the session, closing near the highs of the day partly on technical factors. Most dealers were awaiting the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s release on Friday of unemployment data for November. The consensus is that the report will show an increase of roughly 150,000 jobs, lower than the 233,000 jobs added during the previous month, and an unemployment rate of 5.4 percent. Unfavorable employment data indicate the economy is slowing and could help encourage the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> to lower interest rates. Lower interest rates are bearish for the dollar because they decrease the value of dollar-denominated securities. `` Everybody is convinced that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> -LRB- interest -RRB- rates will go down,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Flanagan </PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZA