<TEXT>
 Here are some of the computer makers that cut jobs in 1989 through layoffs or voluntary separation incentives: <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>: In September announced separation incentive program to eliminate 600 to 1,000 jobs. In December announced new incentive program to eliminate 10,000 more jobs. No layoffs. <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>: In August announced plan to cut 6,000 to 7,000 jobs. In October raised number to about 8,000, composed of 6,300 layoffs and 1,700 reductions through voluntary resignations and early retirement. <ORGANIZATION> Wang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>: Laid off 2,200 employees by the end of September. Last month announced plans for 2,000 more layoffs. <ORGANIZATION> Amdahl </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>: In November announced the layoff of 400 workers in <LOCATION> Sunnyvale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, about 5 percent of its work force. <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>: In September announced elimination of 700 manufacturing jobs in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. Offered retraining and relocation to all affected workers. Anticipated about 200 would instead choose a package of separation incentives. Froze salaries for six months. No layoffs. <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>: In April announced it would exit the supercomputer business and take other steps that would cost 3,100 jobs. <ORGANIZATION> Bull </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> HN </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>: In January the company, then named <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bull </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, announced plans to cut 1,600 jobs through a combination of layoffs and attrition. <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>: In October it announced it would elminate 2,200 jobs, coming on the heels of a reduction in its work force from 16,000 to 14,000 over the past two years. Prime Computer Inc.: Announced in October it would lay off 2,500 workers, or almost 20 percent of its work force, as part of a restructuring of the minicomputer maker after its billion-dollar buyout by J.M. <ORGANIZATION> Whitney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, an investment firm.
