<TEXT>
 Energy futures prices ended mixed Thursday as heating oil staged another weather-related advance. The No. 2 heating oil contract for January delivery shot up 1.01 cents to 65.47 cents a gallon on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The contract traded as high as 65.80 cents during the session after closing up 0.41 cent on Wednesday. Contracts for February through April delivery also gained while longer-term contracts declined. Among other refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale unleaded gasoline for January delivery, which gained 0.33 cent on Wednesday, fell 0.36 cent to finish at 52.81 cents a gallon. Most other contracts also declined. The January contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the main grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, edged up 4 cents to $ 20.51 per 42-gallon barrel. The contract traded as high at $ 20.65 during the session after Wednesday's gain of 13 cents. Other contracts closed mixed. Energy analysts said cold weather as well as strength in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s gasoil market continued to make <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> heating oil attractive to buyers. Heating oil's strength gave the overall market a lift, they said. Low water levels in the <LOCATION> Rhine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> have created problems for barges transporting gasoil, the European version of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> home heating oil. Bullishness in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s gasoil market has trickled into the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market. `` Today saw continued strength in heating oil due to cold weather here and in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the low <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rhine </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Beutel </PERSON>, assistant director of the energy group at <ORGANIZATION> Elders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Redoglio </PERSON>, energy analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION>, said profit-taking helped depress prices in the gasoline pits `` People were selling gas against heating oil,'' <PERSON> Redoglio </PERSON> said.
