<HEAD>Westinghouse Broadcasting Buys Eight Radio Stations for $360 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday it had completed its previously-disclosed plans to buy eight <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan-Legacy </ORGANIZATION> radio stations in a $ 360 million deal that it called the biggest ever in radio. The purchase gives <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> 21 radio stations with an average cumulative audience of 14.1 million people a week, second only to the 15 million-plus commanded by the 21 stations owned by <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cities-ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION>, also known as Group W, is buying the stations from <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Legacy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION>, which are controlled by broadcaster and financier <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> F.X </PERSON> <PERSON> Sillerman </PERSON>. <PERSON> Sillerman </PERSON> and his partners will retain a minority interest in <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> W </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION>, which a source familiar with the deal said was less than 10 percent. Group W, which is an operating unit of <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, announced in April it had agreed to buy 10 <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan-Legacy </ORGANIZATION> stations in a deal reportedly valued at about $ 385 million. But in the meantime, Metropolitan found a local buyer for its two radio stations in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> and they were dropped from the deal with Group W. The newly-acquired statio