<HEAD>Stock Market Plunge Send Precious Metals Higher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Precious metals futures prices rose sharply Thursday on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in reaction to a decline in prices on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. In other markets, grains and soybeans were lower; cotton plunged; livestock and pork futures were mixed, and energy prices were mostly lower. Gold settled $ 4.10 to $ 5.10 higher with the contract for delivery in December at $ 410.00 a troy ounce; silver was 6.5 cents to 7.2 cents higher with December at $ 5.623 a troy ounce. `` The sharp fall in the stock market caused a flight to quality buying ... in the precious metals market,'' said analyst <ORGANIZATION> Jim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Steel noted that many things have caused movement in precious metals prices, including dollar strength or weakness, interest rates and inflation. `` But what has given gold its bold moves -LRB- upward -RRB- have been the declines in the stock market,'' he said Silver prices followed gold in Thursday's upward surge, helped along by the perception that the metal has been sharply oversold in recent sessions, <PERSON> Steel </PERSON> said. Cotton futures were sharply lower on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cotton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as traders had difficulty unloading offerings because of a lack of buyers. At one time, the March contract was down the limit before recovering some losses, said analyst <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitten </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Balfour </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maclaine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Whitten </PERSON> noted that commission houses were active sellers as prices moved below several support levels. Cotton was .23 cent to 1.55 cents lower with December at 63.97 cents a pound. Grain and soybean futures prices closed lower in sluggish trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. The slide in wheat prices was due to the release Wednesday of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s six - to 10-day forecast, which calls for precipitation in the winter wheat crop areas, said analyst <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Leighty </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Wheat futures received little support from news the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> has approved an offer by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for 410,000 metric tons of wheat under the department's Export Enhancement Program. Under the program, private exporters can sell <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commodities at reduced prices to meet foreign competition in some markets and collect free government surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses, or subsidies. Corn futures traded in a narrow range, finishing lower as professionals and commission houses liquidated their long positions. Soybean prices continue to be weighed down by a lack of export business and continuing good planting conditions in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Wheat was -LCB- cent to 2 -RC