<UNK>Manville Suspends Discussions on Stock Repurchase Offer</UNK>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Manville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has announced that it has suspended talks with the <ORGANIZATION> Manville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Personal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Injury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Settlement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> and will not pursue the company's announced offer to repurchase $ 500 million of <ORGANIZATION> Manville </ORGANIZATION> preferred stock from the trust. <ORGANIZATION> Manville </ORGANIZATION> said talks will continue with the trust on ways to improve the trust's financial flexibility and increase value for all shareholders. <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON>, a spokesman for the trust in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, said the trust was trying to raise cash to pay claims. She said <ORGANIZATION> Manville </ORGANIZATION> has stipulations on how stock can be sold to raise money, and <ORGANIZATION> Manville </ORGANIZATION> wanted to buy some of its stock back. However, the two sides disagreed over how much that stock was worth. She said the fund is scheduled to receive profit-sharing funds in 1991 based on 1990 profits, but in the meantime, the fund is running short on cash. `` We're exploring our options,'' she said. <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Manville </ORGANIZATION> wanted to help, `` But we're dealing with reality. We want to do what's right for the trust fund,'' she said. <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Samson </PERSON>, spokesman for the company, said the two sides disagreed on some of the restrictive covenants but declined to be specific. The trust was created as part of <ORGANIZATION> Manville </ORGANIZATION>'s bankruptcy reorganization to compensate victims of asbestos, who had filed suit against the company. The trust was created Nov. 28, 1988, when <ORGANIZATION> Manville </ORGANIZATION> emerged from its Chapter 11 reorganization proceedings. So far, the trust has paid more than 15,000 personal injury claims totaling more than $ 600 million. The trust has assets including 50 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Manville </ORGANIZATION>'s new common stock, convertible preferred stock, a $ 1.8 billion bond, and 20 percent of net profits, beginning in 1992.
