graf pvs, `Analysts pegged...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> stock fell sharply Thursday amid reports of a huge recapitalization plan that would inject up to $ 1 billion into the ailing brokerage. <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> has been under increasing pressure in recent weeks to take steps to improve its profitability and avoid a credit downgrading that would tarnish the firm's reputation and increase its borrowing costs. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which owns 61 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>, reportedly is planning a public sale of 10 million to 22 million shares of <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> stock and a direct investment of about $ 300 million to raise new capital. In addition, <ORGANIZATION> Revlon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Perelman </PERSON> reportedly is holding talks about buying a 9.9 percent stake in <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> for about $ 250 million <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Armour </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> senior vice president, confirmed his company is `` reviewing a number of options'' in regard to <LOCATION> Shearson </LOCATION>. But he said it would be `` inappropriate to discuss any details.'' <PERSON> Armour </PERSON> said the review process has been under way for several weeks. <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON> declined comment on the recapitalization reports. <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> closed down $ 1.75, or about 10.6 percent, at $ 14.75 a share in <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading. The stock rose $ 1.37 -LCB- Wednesday on reports that <PERSON> Perelman </PERSON> might buy up to a 20 percent interest in the company. Analysts pegged Thursday's drop to the lower stake <PERSON> Perelman </PERSON> would have in the latest purported proposal _ reducing the possibility of a takeover _ and to the potential dilution of shares under any new stock issue. ` There's no way the common shareholder comes out well in this,'' said analyst <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Eckenfelder </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> stock has slumped for several months because of poor earnings reports. The company began searching for new capital after <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in October said it was considering downgrading its credit on $ 4.8 billion in long-term <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> debt. Shearson recently began laying off 800 workers, reducing the size of the nation's second-largest brokerage to 35,700, reshuffled its senior management and slashed stockbroker commissions for the first time in 15 years. A downgrading by <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION>'s would increase <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>'s cost of borrowing by about $ 10 million to $ 15 million a year, <PERSON> Eckenfelder </PERSON> said. Securities firms borrow heavily to finance finance trading and other activities. More important, analysts said, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> wants to avoid any loss of reputation. `` There's a sense that it's important for the owners to maintain <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> as a top credit,'' <PERSON> Eckenfelder </PERSON> said. Under the reported recapitalization proposal, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> would reduce its <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> holding to under 50 percent through the new offering and the <PERSON> Perelman </PERSON> deal. That would allow the credit card, travel and financial service company to remove <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> from its financial statements. <PERSON> Eckenfelder </PERSON> said selling securities in a brokerage might prove difficult because of slumping conditions throughout the industry. The proposed recapitalization would dilute the holdings of <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>'s second-largest stockholder, <ORGANIZATION> Nippon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION>, to about 10 percent from 13 percent. The proposal was reported in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> and The <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION>, which cited unidentified sources. Earlier reports said <PERSON> Perelman </PERSON> would have been able to obtain about 20 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>'s stock if he exercised all of his stock options under the deal as originally proposed. But the Times said the proposed transaction was altered to make it less complex. While any such deal would provide needed capital for <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>, some analysts have cautioned that further dividing the ownership of Shearson among three or more large outsiders could prove to be a headache for executives under pressure to turn around the firm's slumping profits <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION>'s said it was mulling a possible credit rating downgrade for <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>'s bonds and commercial paper due to the firm's low level of capital, low profits and exposure in commercial real estate loans and investments, as well as the general slump in brokerage activity.
