<HEAD>First Interstate Announces Plan to Dump Problem Assets in Texas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bancorp </ORGANIZATION>, hammered by loan losses at out-of-state subsidiaries, said Thursday it would speed up its program to sell bad loans in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and add $ 400 million to its reserves to cover the costs. First Interstate, whose <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> unit lost $ 174 million last quarter and whose <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> subsidiary also has shown big losses in the past, also said it intended to offer 7.5 million shares of new common stock to raise about $ 400 million. First Interstate, the nation's largest retail banking system with offices in 21 states, said the program will cut the costs of carrying the bad loans. That, combined with existing unused tax benefits, should provide up to $ 367 million of potential future tax benefits, the company said. Of the $ 400 million in added reserves, $ 300 million was to go toward the program to eliminate the bad loans in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, and another $ 100 million `` to address the risk inherent in the company's real estate portfolio.'' First Interstate showed a loss of $ 15.5 million last quarter, or 57 cents per share, after its <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> took a $ 350 million provision for loan losses due to plunging real estate values in the state. It was the first quarterly loss for the big holding company since the third quarter of 1988, when <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> posted a $ 214 million loss because of loan losses in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> banking operations and restructuring.
