<HEAD>Analyst: Government Report Sees `Potential Problems' At Drug Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The price of <ORGANIZATION> Abbott </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> stock slipped Thursday after a brokerage firm said a government report showed one of the company's drug plants might be `` a little sloppy'' in adhering to federal standards. <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON> stock closed at $ 67.12 -LCB- a share, down $ 1.25, in <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading. `` We did n't tell people to sell, we just said here is some information about something that is going on,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Harshbarger </PERSON>, vice president and senior health care analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a brokerage. A day earlier, <PERSON> Harshbarger </PERSON> obtained through the Freedom of Information Act a copy of a 41-page <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> report on an <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON> facility in <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> that produces drugs given intravenously. `` Our consultants pointed out where it looked like standards had been becoming a little sloppy _ where it looked like there could be potential problems,'' <PERSON> Harshbarger </PERSON> said. He said 56 citations were listed in the report, written after an <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> inspection July 5 through Nov. 3 at the plant. He said 80 percent of the issues cited were `` nit-picking, minor problems and 20 percent potentially had some serious implications.'' He declined to be specific. <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Ekvall </PERSON>, consumer affairs officer at the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> regional office, said: `` The only thing we can say at this point is it's an ongoing investigation. This report is observations, and from it the regulatory people have to determine what type of regulatory action has to be taken.'' <PERSON> Harshbarger </PERSON> said the brokerage firm's sales staff was told in a meeting Thursday morning to advise clients of the report. <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Babington </PERSON> said later Thursday that the report's observations were technical in nature, but she did n't elaborate `` The bottom line for customers and patients is that the products are safe and they are effective for what they are intended to be used for,'' <PERSON> Babington </PERSON> said. She said the plant referred to in the report is `` one small section of one building on an <LOCATION> Abbott </LOCATION> campus that has many, many facilities.''
