<HEAD>Dollar Up, Share Prices Fall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning figures, comments.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar was up against the Japanese yen Friday morning, while share prices on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> declined in morning trading. The dollar closed the morning session at 144.23 yen, down from its opening of 144.32 yen but up 0.12 yen from Thursday's close here of 144.13 yen. It was traded in a narrow range of 144.21 to 144.40 yen. The dollar's higher opening in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> followed a similar overnight upswing in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, where it ended at 144.30 yen. The mark was dropping back against the dollar after sales of the German currency by <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> speculators in <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Minori </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeuchi </PERSON>, a trader at <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. Some speculators in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> seemed to be waiting until the dollar rose more before selling to buy yen, <PERSON> Takeuchi </PERSON> said. Japanese Finance Minister <PERSON> Ryutaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Hashimoto </PERSON> indicated a relative lack of concern with the dollar's strength above the 144.00 yen level at a regular press conference Friday morning. `` Inside a delicate situation we are taking a delicate look,'' he said. The remark was seen as indicating the ministry is not alarmed by the dollar's recent rise. Most market players were awaiting the release of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> jobless rate for November due out in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> later Friday, traders said. On the stock exchange, the 225-issue <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> lost 103.09 points, or 0.27 percent, closing the morning session at 37,755.02. It had gained 203.82 points to a record-high closing of 37,858.11 Thursday. A trader at <ORGAN