 Federal regulators have approved a $ 450 million capital infusion from <ORGANIZATION> Pinnacle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to its troubled <ORGANIZATION> MeraBank </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary, the thrift's chairman said late Wednesday. `` This is an important beginning of the recapitalization of <ORGANIZATION> MeraBank </ORGANIZATION>. It means about $ 45 million a year in interest revenue,'' said Chairman <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>. However, the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said the transfer was an ominous sign for <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Serivce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the state's largest public utility and <PERSON> Pinnacle </PERSON> <PERSON> West </PERSON>'s only profitable subsidiary for the past two years. Pinnacle West, a $ 13 billion-a-year, Phoenix-based holding company, was founded to run <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. On Friday, <ORGANIZATION> PacifiCorp </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION> utility holding company, announced it wanted to buy Pinnacle West in a deal valued at about $ 1.87 billion. The bid, which is conditioned upon Pinnacle West disposing of <ORGANIZATION> MeraBank </ORGANIZATION>, is an expansion of an earlier offer from <ORGANIZATION> PacifiCorp </ORGANIZATION> to buy <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. Pinnacle West created concern in 1986 when it bought <ORGANIZATION> MeraBank </ORGANIZATION> just as the problems that have plagued <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> savings and loans became most acute. The acquisition was criticized because of the possibility that the S & amp; L could siphon funds from the utility company, a robust dividend-producer. Pinnacle West has repeatedly denied any shifting of funds among its subsidiaries. `` The settlement announced tonight ... saddles Pinnacle West with additional debt at a time when the company can ill afford it and leaves ownership of <ORGANIZATION> MeraBank </ORGANIZATION> in the hands of Pinnacle West with no assurance that losses will not continue to mount,'' said <PERSON> Renz </PERSON> <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON>, chairman of the corporation commission, in a statement. He said the regulatory commission was worried about `` the possibility that <LOCATION> Pinnacle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> creditors will look to <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> for repayment.'' `` This commission has moved in the past to prevent the parent company from draining the resources of <ORGANIZATION> APS </ORGANIZATION> at the expense of ratepayers, and -LRB- the commission -RRB- will do so again without hesitation or reservation,'' <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> added. Pinnacle West Chairman <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Turley </PERSON> said the company and the <ORGANIZATION> federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thrift </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supervision </ORGANIZATION> office in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> agreed that <ORGANIZATION> Pinnacle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> will pay <ORGANIZATION> MeraBank </ORGANIZATION> $ 300 million in cash and accrued interest by March 31, 1990. Pinnacle West also said it will give the thrift an unsecured note for $ 150 million. <PERSON> Turley </PERSON> did not address the concerns over <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORG